1
00:01:38,807 --> 00:01:40,141
No!

2
00:04:30,354 --> 00:04:32,647
I'm requesting… I am…

3
00:04:32,814 --> 00:04:36,317
Captain, I'd like to request that it be me who's the attorney…

4
00:04:37,361 --> 00:04:39,946
That it be myself who's assigned…

5
00:04:40,197 --> 00:04:43,324
No, I'd like to request that it be I who am assigned…

6
00:04:44,534 --> 00:04:49,372
That it be I who am assigned? That's confidence-inspiring.

7
00:04:50,207 --> 00:04:56,087
Good grammar there. Captain, I'd like to request that I be the attorney assigned…

8
00:05:00,133 --> 00:05:02,718
Hi, I'm Lieutenant Commander Galloway. I'm here to see Captain West.

9
00:05:02,886 --> 00:05:04,178
Go right in, commander, they're expecting you.

10
00:05:04,346 --> 00:05:05,388
Thank you.

11
00:05:09,559 --> 00:05:12,853
Jo, come on in. Thank you, sir.

12
00:05:13,021 --> 00:05:15,398
Captain West, this is Lieutenant Commander Galloway.

13
00:05:15,565 --> 00:05:17,858
Jo, you know Commander Lawrence? Yes, sir.

14
00:05:18,026 --> 00:05:19,735
Captain, I appreciate you seeing me on such short notice.

15
00:05:19,903 --> 00:05:21,112
Would you like to sit down?

16
00:05:21,405 --> 00:05:23,739
I'm fine, sir. Have a seat.

17
00:05:23,907 --> 00:05:25,241
Okay.

18
00:05:25,409 --> 00:05:27,493
I understand we had some trouble over the weekend down in Cuba?

19
00:05:27,661 --> 00:05:30,246
Uh, yes, sir. This past Friday.

20
00:05:30,414 --> 00:05:34,917
Two Marines, a Lance Corporal Harold Dawson and a Private Louden Downey,

21
00:05:35,085 --> 00:05:39,088
entered the barracks room of a PFC William Santiago and assaulted him.

22
00:05:39,381 --> 00:05:42,758
Santiago died at the base hospital approximately an hour later.

23
00:05:43,010 --> 00:05:46,387
The NIS agent who took Dawson and Downey's statements

24
00:05:46,555 --> 00:05:48,806
maintains they were trying to prevent Santiago

25
00:05:48,974 --> 00:05:51,642
from naming Dawson in a fenceline shooting incident.

26
00:05:51,810 --> 00:05:55,438
They're scheduled to have a hearing down in Cuba this afternoon at 1600.

27
00:05:55,605 --> 00:05:56,772
What's the problem?

28
00:05:56,940 --> 00:05:59,442
Dawson and Downey are both recruiting-poster Marines.

29
00:05:59,609 --> 00:06:01,902
Santiago was known to be a screwup.

30
00:06:02,070 --> 00:06:04,739
I was thinking it sounded an awful lot like a Code Red.

31
00:06:05,782 --> 00:06:07,116
Christ!

32
00:06:07,284 --> 00:06:10,870
Sir, I'd like to have them moved up to Washington and assigned counsel.

33
00:06:11,038 --> 00:06:13,122
Someone who can really look into this.

34
00:06:13,290 --> 00:06:15,624
Someone who possesses not only the legal skill

35
00:06:15,834 --> 00:06:18,627
but a familiarity with the inner workings of the military.

36
00:06:18,795 --> 00:06:23,424
In short, captain, I'd like to suggest that I be the one who that…

37
00:06:23,592 --> 00:06:28,679
That it be me who is assigned to represent them, myself.

38
00:06:30,599 --> 00:06:35,144
Why don't you get a cup of coffee? Thank you, sir, I'm fine.

39
00:06:35,312 --> 00:06:38,439
I'd like you to leave the room, so we can talk about you behind your back.

40
00:06:39,107 --> 00:06:41,067
Certainly, sir.

41
00:06:47,491 --> 00:06:50,159
I thought this Code Red shit wasn't going on anymore.

42
00:06:50,327 --> 00:06:53,454
With the Marines at Gitmo, who knows what the hell goes on down there?

43
00:06:53,622 --> 00:06:57,458
We'd better find out before the rest of the world does. Damn thing could get messy.

44
00:06:57,667 --> 00:07:00,169
What about this Commander Galloway?

45
00:07:00,337 --> 00:07:05,257
She's been working a desk at Internal Affairs for, what, a little over a year now.

46
00:07:05,425 --> 00:07:06,425
Before that?

47
00:07:06,593 --> 00:07:08,469
She disposed of three cases in two years.

48
00:07:08,678 --> 00:07:11,347
Three cases in two years? Who's she handling, the Rosenbergs?

49
00:07:11,515 --> 00:07:14,016
She's not cut out for litigation. She's a hell of an investigator…

50
00:07:14,184 --> 00:07:17,436
In Internal Affairs, sure. She can crawl up a lawyer's ass with the best of them.

51
00:07:17,604 --> 00:07:18,687
When it comes to trial work…

52
00:07:18,855 --> 00:07:22,858
I know, I know, all passion, no street smarts. Bring her back in.

53
00:07:28,532 --> 00:07:29,740
Jo.

54
00:07:34,121 --> 00:07:36,789
We're gonna have the defendants moved up here in the morning.

55
00:07:36,957 --> 00:07:37,957
Thank you, sir.

56
00:07:38,125 --> 00:07:40,126
And I'll have Division assign them counsel.

57
00:07:41,211 --> 00:07:43,921
But not me?

58
00:07:44,131 --> 00:07:47,508
Well, from what I understand from your colleagues, you're much too valuable

59
00:07:47,676 --> 00:07:50,553
to be wasted on what I'm sure will boil down to a five-minute plea bargain

60
00:07:50,720 --> 00:07:52,138
and a week's worth of paperwork.

61
00:07:52,305 --> 00:07:55,683
Sir, there might be more involved. Don't worry about it.

62
00:07:55,892 --> 00:07:58,811
I promise you, Division will assign the right man for the job.

63
00:07:58,979 --> 00:08:01,230
All right, let's go, let's get two!

64
00:08:02,816 --> 00:08:03,816
Sorry.

65
00:08:03,984 --> 00:08:07,236
Nothing to be sorry about, Sherby. Look the ball into your glove.

66
00:08:07,654 --> 00:08:11,490
Shooting two. Sorry.

67
00:08:11,700 --> 00:08:16,412
You gotta trust me, Sherby. Keep your eyes open, your chances of catching increase by 10.

68
00:08:16,580 --> 00:08:18,247
Kaffee. Let's try it again.

69
00:08:18,415 --> 00:08:21,417
Kaffee! Dave, you seem distraught.

70
00:08:21,585 --> 00:08:23,711
We were supposed to meet in your office 15 minutes ago.

71
00:08:23,879 --> 00:08:25,754
You're stalling on the McDermott case.

72
00:08:25,922 --> 00:08:30,718
We either get it done now, or I'll hang your boy from a fucking yardarm!

73
00:08:30,886 --> 00:08:34,763
Yardarm? Sherby, does the Navy still hang people from yardarms?

74
00:08:34,931 --> 00:08:36,098
I don't think so.

75
00:08:36,558 --> 00:08:39,685
Sherby doesn't think the Navy does that anymore.

76
00:08:39,853 --> 00:08:43,105
I'll charge him with possession and being under the influence while on duty.

77
00:08:43,273 --> 00:08:47,443
You plead guilty, I'll recommend 30 days in the brig with loss of rank and pay.

78
00:08:47,611 --> 00:08:52,406
It was 10 dollars' worth of oregano. Your client thought it was marijuana.

79
00:08:52,574 --> 00:08:55,201
My client's a moron. That's not against the law.

80
00:08:55,368 --> 00:08:58,621
I got people to answer to. I'm gonna charge him.

81
00:08:58,830 --> 00:09:01,790
With possession of a condiment? Kaffee.

82
00:09:01,958 --> 00:09:06,253
I tried to help you out of this, but if you ask for jail time, I'll file a motion to dismiss.

83
00:09:06,421 --> 00:09:08,297
You won't get it. I will get it.

84
00:09:08,465 --> 00:09:13,010
If not, I'll file a motion seeking to obtain an evidentiary ruling in advance,

85
00:09:13,303 --> 00:09:15,763
and after that I'll file against pre-trial confinement.

86
00:09:15,972 --> 00:09:18,307
You'll spend the next three months going blind on paperwork,

87
00:09:18,475 --> 00:09:21,977
because a signalman bought and smoked a dime bag of oregano.

88
00:09:22,312 --> 00:09:24,480
Let's go! Let's get two!

89
00:09:25,649 --> 00:09:30,402
Twenty days in the brig. Fifteen days' restricted duty.

90
00:09:31,988 --> 00:09:33,906
I don't know why I'm agreeing to this.

91
00:09:34,074 --> 00:09:36,242
Because you have wisdom beyond your years.

92
00:09:40,288 --> 00:09:43,457
- Good morning. - Good morning, captain.

93
00:09:43,625 --> 00:09:45,167
How's the baby, Sam?

94
00:09:45,335 --> 00:09:48,462
I think she's getting ready to say her first word any day now.

95
00:09:48,630 --> 00:09:50,047
How can you tell?

96
00:09:50,257 --> 00:09:53,842
She just looks like she has something to say.

97
00:09:54,636 --> 00:09:56,512
Excuse me, sorry I'm late.

98
00:09:56,680 --> 00:10:00,683
I know you don't have a good excuse, so I won't force you to come up with a bad one.

99
00:10:00,850 --> 00:10:05,062
Thank you, sir. This first one's for you.

100
00:10:05,272 --> 00:10:09,149
You're moving up in the world. You've been requested by Division.

101
00:10:09,317 --> 00:10:10,359
Uh-oh.

102
00:10:10,527 --> 00:10:14,405
Requested to do what? Guantánamo Bay, Cuba.

103
00:10:14,572 --> 00:10:17,366
A Marine Corporal named Dawson illegally fires a round

104
00:10:17,534 --> 00:10:21,412
from his weapon, over the fenceline and into Cuban territory.

105
00:10:21,705 --> 00:10:23,455
What's a fenceline? Sam.

106
00:10:23,873 --> 00:10:27,710
A big wall separating the good guys from the bad guys.

107
00:10:27,877 --> 00:10:29,211
Teacher's pet.

108
00:10:29,379 --> 00:10:32,298
PFC William Santiago threatens to rat on Dawson

109
00:10:32,465 --> 00:10:34,508
to the Naval Investigative Service.

110
00:10:34,676 --> 00:10:38,387
Dawson and another member of his squad, PFC Louden Downey,

111
00:10:38,555 --> 00:10:41,724
go into Santiago's room, tie him up,

112
00:10:41,891 --> 00:10:44,184
stuff a rag down his throat,

113
00:10:44,352 --> 00:10:46,228
and an hour later, Santiago's dead.

114
00:10:46,396 --> 00:10:50,149
Attending physician says the rag was treated with some kind of toxin.

115
00:10:50,317 --> 00:10:52,901
They poisoned the rag? Not according to them.

116
00:10:53,069 --> 00:10:55,404
What do they say? Not much.

117
00:10:55,697 --> 00:10:58,407
They're being flown up tomorrow. On Wednesday at 0600,

118
00:10:58,575 --> 00:11:02,578
you'll catch a transport down to Cuba for the day to find out what you can.

119
00:11:02,746 --> 00:11:06,874
Meantime, go and see Lieutenant Commander JoAnne Galloway

120
00:11:07,792 --> 00:11:09,543
with Internal Affairs.

121
00:11:09,753 --> 00:11:12,254
Any questions? The flight to Cuba,

122
00:11:12,422 --> 00:11:15,257
was that 0600 in the morning, sir?

123
00:11:16,468 --> 00:11:21,263
Seems important to Division that this one be handled by the book, so I'm assigning co-counsel.

124
00:11:21,431 --> 00:11:22,890
Any volunteers?

125
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:25,434
No. Sam…

126
00:11:25,602 --> 00:11:28,854
Sir, I got a stack of papers… Work with Kaffee on this.

127
00:11:29,022 --> 00:11:31,857
Doing what? He'll have this done in four days.

128
00:11:32,025 --> 00:11:37,196
Doing various administrative things. Backup. Whatever.

129
00:11:37,364 --> 00:11:39,907
In other words, I have no responsibilities?

130
00:11:40,075 --> 00:11:41,200
Right.

131
00:11:41,368 --> 00:11:43,494
My kind of case.

132
00:11:44,788 --> 00:11:49,249
Right. Right. Okay, but I gotta have that report by Wednesday.

133
00:11:55,673 --> 00:11:58,300
Hi. Hold on. Hi.

134
00:11:58,468 --> 00:12:02,638
Daniel Kaffee. I was told to meet with, uh…

135
00:12:08,311 --> 00:12:11,105
Lieutenant Commander Galloway.

136
00:12:13,483 --> 00:12:17,611
About a briefing. I'll call you back.

137
00:12:19,614 --> 00:12:21,281
You're the attorney Division assigned?

138
00:12:22,242 --> 00:12:24,201
I'm lead counsel, this is Sam Weinberg.

139
00:12:24,411 --> 00:12:28,622
I have no responsibilities whatsoever. Come in, please. Have a seat.

140
00:12:39,175 --> 00:12:41,176
Lieutenant, how long have you been in the Navy?

141
00:12:43,054 --> 00:12:44,805
Going on nine months now.

142
00:12:45,557 --> 00:12:48,517
And how long have you been out of law school?

143
00:12:48,685 --> 00:12:50,144
Little over a year.

144
00:12:50,311 --> 00:12:53,939
I see. Have I done something wrong?

145
00:12:54,107 --> 00:12:57,192
No. It's just that when I petitioned Division to have counsel assigned,

146
00:12:57,360 --> 00:12:59,445
I was hoping I would be taken seriously.

147
00:13:00,029 --> 00:13:02,197
No offense taken, in case you were wondering.

148
00:13:02,365 --> 00:13:06,368
Lieutenant Kaffee is generally considered the best litigator in our office.

149
00:13:06,536 --> 00:13:09,872
He successfully plea-bargained 44 cases in nine months.

150
00:13:10,039 --> 00:13:13,834
One more, I get a set of steak knives. Have you ever been in a courtroom?

151
00:13:14,002 --> 00:13:15,836
I once had my driver's license suspended…

152
00:13:16,004 --> 00:13:18,422
Danny. If this thing goes to court,

153
00:13:18,590 --> 00:13:20,716
they won't need a lawyer, they'll need a priest.

154
00:13:21,342 --> 00:13:24,386
No, they'll need a lawyer.

155
00:13:24,554 --> 00:13:30,017
Dawson's family's been contacted. Downey's closest relative is his aunt on his mother's side.

156
00:13:30,185 --> 00:13:32,978
She hasn't been contacted yet, would you like me to do that?

157
00:13:33,146 --> 00:13:34,563
Sure, if you feel like it.

158
00:13:36,399 --> 00:13:40,402
One of the people you'll be seeing is the barracks CO, Colonel Nathan Jessep.

159
00:13:40,570 --> 00:13:42,613
I assume you've heard of him.

160
00:13:42,780 --> 00:13:45,199
Who hasn't?

161
00:13:45,366 --> 00:13:46,909
He's been in the papers lately.

162
00:13:47,076 --> 00:13:48,994
He's expected to be director of operations

163
00:13:49,162 --> 00:13:51,288
of the National Security Council. Really?

164
00:13:51,456 --> 00:13:54,416
These are the letters that Santiago wrote in his eight months at Gitmo.

165
00:13:54,584 --> 00:13:57,252
That's Guantánamo Bay. I knew that one.

166
00:13:57,420 --> 00:13:58,921
He wrote the fleet commander, HQ Atlantic,

167
00:13:59,088 --> 00:14:02,090
the Marine commandant, even his senator.

168
00:14:02,258 --> 00:14:05,552
He wanted to be transferred off the base. No one was listening. Are you with me?

169
00:14:05,720 --> 00:14:07,262
Yeah.

170
00:14:08,723 --> 00:14:10,933
Finally he wrote the Naval Investigative Service,

171
00:14:11,100 --> 00:14:16,563
where he offered to trade information about Dawson's shooting for a transfer.

172
00:14:17,232 --> 00:14:19,274
Right. Is that all?

173
00:14:19,442 --> 00:14:23,779
This letter makes it look like your client had a motive to kill Santiago.

174
00:14:23,947 --> 00:14:28,784
Got you. And Santiago is who? The victim.

175
00:14:28,952 --> 00:14:30,285
Write that down.

176
00:14:30,453 --> 00:14:34,456
Am I correct in assuming that these letters don't paint a flattering picture of Marine Corps life at Gitmo?

177
00:14:34,624 --> 00:14:35,958
Yes, amon… And am I further right

178
00:14:36,125 --> 00:14:39,878
that a protracted investigation might embarrass the Security Council guy?

179
00:14:40,046 --> 00:14:42,673
Colonel Jessep… DANNY: Twelve years.

180
00:14:42,840 --> 00:14:43,966
I'm sorry?

181
00:14:44,133 --> 00:14:48,053
I'll get them to drop conspiracy and conduct unbecoming. Twelve years.

182
00:14:48,680 --> 00:14:51,723
You haven't talked to a witness or looked at a piece of paper.

183
00:14:52,141 --> 00:14:53,892
Pretty impressive, huh?

184
00:14:54,060 --> 00:14:55,644
You're gonna have to go deeper than that.

185
00:14:55,812 --> 00:14:58,480
Do you have some jurisdiction here I should know about?

186
00:14:58,648 --> 00:15:01,275
My job is to make sure that you do your job.

187
00:15:01,442 --> 00:15:06,822
I'm special counsel for Internal Affairs. So my jurisdiction's pretty much in your face.

188
00:15:09,075 --> 00:15:12,077
Read the letters. I'll expect a report when you return from Cuba.

189
00:15:12,620 --> 00:15:14,830
Sure. You're dismissed!

190
00:15:17,041 --> 00:15:19,418
I always forget that part.

191
00:15:21,337 --> 00:15:23,714
He's a little preoccupied.

192
00:15:23,881 --> 00:15:26,842
Team's playing Bethesda Medical next week.

193
00:15:27,010 --> 00:15:31,597
Tell your friend not to get cute down there. The Marines in Guantánamo are fanatical.

194
00:15:31,764 --> 00:15:34,600
About what? About being Marines.

195
00:15:36,644 --> 00:15:39,313
Dear sir, my name is PFC William T. Santiago.

196
00:15:39,480 --> 00:15:41,523
I'm a Marine stationed at Marine barracks,

197
00:15:41,691 --> 00:15:45,152
Rifle Security Company Windward, 2nd Platoon Bravo.

198
00:15:45,320 --> 00:15:48,822
L am writing to inform you of my problems with my unit here in Cuba

199
00:15:48,990 --> 00:15:50,574
and to ask for your help.

200
00:15:50,742 --> 00:15:56,038
I've fallen out of runs before for several reasons, such as feeling dizzy or nauseated.

201
00:15:56,205 --> 00:15:59,791
But on May 18th, I'd fallen back about 20 or 30 yards

202
00:15:59,959 --> 00:16:02,502
going down a rocky, unstable hill.

203
00:16:02,670 --> 00:16:05,422
My sergeant grabbed me and pushed me down the hill,

204
00:16:05,590 --> 00:16:09,426
then I saw all black and the last thing I remember is hitting the deck.

205
00:16:09,636 --> 00:16:12,846
L was brought to the hospital, where I was told I just had heat exhaustion.

206
00:16:13,014 --> 00:16:18,101
L ask you to help me. Please, sir, I just need to be transferred out of RSC.

207
00:16:18,269 --> 00:16:22,689
Sincerely, PFC William T. Santiago, U.S. Marine Corps.

208
00:16:22,857 --> 00:16:26,860
P.S. ln exchange for my transfer off the base, I'm willing to provide you…

209
00:16:27,028 --> 00:16:32,074
… with information about an illegal fenceline shooting that occurred the night of August the 2nd.

210
00:16:33,076 --> 00:16:37,371
Who the fuck is PFC William T. Santiago?

211
00:16:37,580 --> 00:16:40,582
Private Santiago's a member of 2nd Platoon Bravo, sir.

212
00:16:40,750 --> 00:16:44,920
Yeah. Apparently he's not very happy down here at Shangri-la,

213
00:16:45,088 --> 00:16:49,925
because he's written letters to everybody but Santa Claus, asking for a transfer.

214
00:16:50,093 --> 00:16:55,597
Now he's telling tales about a fenceline shooting. Matthew?

215
00:16:56,057 --> 00:17:01,478
I'm appalled, sir. You're appalled.

216
00:17:02,563 --> 00:17:05,941
This kid broke the chain of command and ratted on a member of his unit,

217
00:17:06,109 --> 00:17:09,319
to say nothing of the fact that he is a U.S. Marine,

218
00:17:09,487 --> 00:17:14,616
and it would appear he can't run from here to there without collapsing from heat exhaustion.

219
00:17:14,784 --> 00:17:17,953
What the fuck is going on in Bravo company, Matthew?

220
00:17:18,121 --> 00:17:21,039
Colonel, I think perhaps it would be better to hold this discussion in private.

221
00:17:21,207 --> 00:17:25,252
That won't be necessary. I can handle this situation, sir.

222
00:17:25,420 --> 00:17:27,754
Like you handled Curtis Bell? Sir, your methods…

223
00:17:27,922 --> 00:17:29,047
Don't interrupt me, lieutenant.

224
00:17:29,215 --> 00:17:30,590
I'm still your superior officer.

225
00:17:30,758 --> 00:17:32,634
And I'm yours, Matthew.

226
00:17:34,637 --> 00:17:37,889
I wanna know what we're going to do about this.

227
00:17:38,057 --> 00:17:40,892
I think Santiago should be transferred off the base immediately.

228
00:17:41,060 --> 00:17:42,644
He's that bad, huh?

229
00:17:42,812 --> 00:17:46,815
Not only that, but word of this letter's bound to get out, and he's gonna get his ass whipped.

230
00:17:47,108 --> 00:17:52,779
Hmm. Transfer Santiago? Yes.

231
00:17:52,947 --> 00:17:57,075
Sure, you're right. I'm sure that's the thing to do.

232
00:17:58,828 --> 00:18:02,831
Wait. Wait, I've got a better idea.

233
00:18:02,999 --> 00:18:06,793
Let's transfer the whole squad off the base. Let's…

234
00:18:06,961 --> 00:18:09,004
On second thought, Windward.

235
00:18:09,172 --> 00:18:13,300
Let's transfer the whole Windward division off the base.

236
00:18:13,468 --> 00:18:18,722
Jon, go get those boys down off the fence. They're packing their bags.

237
00:18:18,890 --> 00:18:21,433
Tom! Sir?

238
00:18:21,601 --> 00:18:23,477
Get me the president on the phone.

239
00:18:23,644 --> 00:18:26,271
We're surrendering our position in Cuba.

240
00:18:26,439 --> 00:18:28,774
- Yes, sir. - Wait a minute, Tom.

241
00:18:28,941 --> 00:18:34,696
Don't get the president just yet. Maybe we should consider this for a second.

242
00:18:34,864 --> 00:18:36,823
Dismissed, Tom. Yes, sir.

243
00:18:38,201 --> 00:18:41,870
Maybe… And I'm just spit-balling here.

244
00:18:42,038 --> 00:18:46,875
Maybe we have a responsibility as officers to train Santiago.

245
00:18:47,084 --> 00:18:51,338
Maybe we, as officers, have a responsibility to this country

246
00:18:51,506 --> 00:18:54,925
to see that the men and women charged with its security

247
00:18:55,092 --> 00:18:56,885
are trained professionals.

248
00:18:57,053 --> 00:19:00,722
Yes, I'm certain that I read that somewhere once.

249
00:19:00,890 --> 00:19:03,475
And now I'm thinking, Colonel Markinson,

250
00:19:03,643 --> 00:19:07,729
that your suggestion of transferring Santiago,

251
00:19:07,897 --> 00:19:11,107
while expeditious and certainly painless,

252
00:19:11,317 --> 00:19:16,613
might not be, in a manner of speaking, the American way.

253
00:19:16,823 --> 00:19:21,076
Santiago stays where he is.

254
00:19:21,244 --> 00:19:26,456
We're gonna train the lad. Jon, you're in charge.

255
00:19:26,624 --> 00:19:29,584
Santiago doesn't make 4.6, 4.6

256
00:19:29,752 --> 00:19:33,421
on his next proficiency and conduct report,

257
00:19:33,589 --> 00:19:35,924
and I'm going to blame you.

258
00:19:36,092 --> 00:19:38,552
Then I'm going to kill you. Yes, sir.

259
00:19:38,928 --> 00:19:41,221
I think that's a mistake, colonel.

260
00:19:42,765 --> 00:19:46,935
Matthew, I think I will have that word in private with you now.

261
00:19:47,103 --> 00:19:50,772
Jon, that's all. Why don't we meet at the O Club and have lunch,

262
00:19:50,940 --> 00:19:53,650
and we'll talk about the training of young William.

263
00:19:53,860 --> 00:19:56,528
I'd be delighted to hear your suggestions.

264
00:19:56,696 --> 00:19:58,947
Dismissed. Yes, sir.

265
00:20:02,243 --> 00:20:05,287
Matthew, sit down. Please.

266
00:20:10,793 --> 00:20:13,044
What do you think of Kendrick?

267
00:20:13,212 --> 00:20:14,963
Nathan, I don't think my opinion of Kendrick…

268
00:20:15,131 --> 00:20:18,300
I think he's pretty much of a weasel myself.

269
00:20:18,467 --> 00:20:20,260
But he's an awfully good officer,

270
00:20:20,428 --> 00:20:24,764
and in the end, we see eye to eye on the best way to run a Marine unit.

271
00:20:24,974 --> 00:20:28,310
We're in the business of saving lives, Matthew.

272
00:20:28,477 --> 00:20:32,147
That is a responsibility that we have to take pretty seriously.

273
00:20:32,315 --> 00:20:36,526
And I believe that taking a Marine who is not quite up to the job

274
00:20:36,694 --> 00:20:41,156
and shipping him off to another assignment puts lives in danger.

275
00:20:41,991 --> 00:20:44,159
Sit down, Matthew.

276
00:20:53,794 --> 00:20:55,921
We go back a while.

277
00:20:56,088 --> 00:20:58,214
We went to the Academy together,

278
00:20:58,382 --> 00:21:01,843
we were commissioned together, did our tours in Vietnam together.

279
00:21:02,428 --> 00:21:07,974
But I've been promoted up through the chain with greater speed and success than you have.

280
00:21:08,142 --> 00:21:12,145
Now, if that's a source of tension or embarrassment for you,

281
00:21:12,313 --> 00:21:14,189
I don't give a shit.

282
00:21:14,357 --> 00:21:19,569
We're in the business of saving lives, Lieutenant Colonel Markinson.

283
00:21:19,737 --> 00:21:23,615
Don't ever question my orders in front of another officer.

284
00:21:43,594 --> 00:21:46,680
All the paperwork's in order. Step over there.

285
00:21:46,847 --> 00:21:48,765
Yes, sir.

286
00:21:52,770 --> 00:21:56,815
Hal, is this Washington D.C.? All right, let's move.

287
00:21:56,983 --> 00:21:58,775
Yes, sir.

288
00:22:05,992 --> 00:22:07,450
Got all of that one.

289
00:22:07,618 --> 00:22:12,205
Excuse me. I wanted to talk to you about Dawson and Downey.

290
00:22:12,373 --> 00:22:16,126
Say again? Dawson and Downey.

291
00:22:16,293 --> 00:22:18,169
Those names sound like they should mean something to me, but…

292
00:22:18,421 --> 00:22:21,047
Dawson. Downey. Your clients?

293
00:22:21,215 --> 00:22:24,426
The Cuba thing! Yes! Oh, Dawson and Downey. Right.

294
00:22:27,263 --> 00:22:29,681
I've done something wrong again, haven't I?

295
00:22:29,849 --> 00:22:34,602
I was wondering why two guys have been locked up since this morning while their lawyer's out hitting a ball.

296
00:22:36,772 --> 00:22:39,941
We need the practice. That wasn't funny.

297
00:22:40,693 --> 00:22:42,068
It was a little funny.

298
00:22:42,236 --> 00:22:47,490
Lieutenant, would you be very insulted if I recommended different counsel?

299
00:22:47,658 --> 00:22:50,952
Why? I don't think you're fit to handle it.

300
00:22:51,579 --> 00:22:57,459
You don't even know me. Ordinarily it takes someone hours to find that out.

301
00:22:59,670 --> 00:23:02,589
Oh, come on. That was damn funny.

302
00:23:05,593 --> 00:23:09,846
You're wrong. I do know you.

303
00:23:10,056 --> 00:23:13,475
Daniel Alistair Kaffee, born June 8th, 1964,

304
00:23:13,642 --> 00:23:15,602
at Boston Mercy Hospital.

305
00:23:15,770 --> 00:23:22,317
Your father's Lionel Kaffee, former Attorney General of the U.S., died 1985.

306
00:23:22,568 --> 00:23:25,320
You went to Harvard Law, then joined the Navy,

307
00:23:25,488 --> 00:23:27,989
probably because that's what your father wanted.

308
00:23:28,157 --> 00:23:31,785
Now you're just treading water for the three years in the JAG corps,

309
00:23:31,952 --> 00:23:34,954
just laying low till you can get out and get a real job.

310
00:23:35,122 --> 00:23:38,583
If that's the situation, that's fine, I won't tell anyone.

311
00:23:38,751 --> 00:23:43,713
But if this case is handled in the same fast-food, slick-assed, Persian-bazaar manner

312
00:23:43,881 --> 00:23:47,550
with which you seem to handle everything else, then something's gonna get missed.

313
00:23:47,718 --> 00:23:52,889
And I wouldn't be doing my job if I allowed Dawson and Downey to sit in prison

314
00:23:53,099 --> 00:23:57,519
because their attorney predetermined the path of least resistance.

315
00:23:59,021 --> 00:24:00,730
Wow.

316
00:24:01,398 --> 00:24:04,025
I'm sexually aroused, commander.

317
00:24:04,693 --> 00:24:06,945
I don't think your clients murdered anyone.

318
00:24:07,113 --> 00:24:10,365
What are you basing this on? There was no intent.

319
00:24:10,533 --> 00:24:13,243
Doctor's report says that Santiago died of asphyxiation

320
00:24:13,410 --> 00:24:15,078
brought on by acute lactic acidosis,

321
00:24:15,246 --> 00:24:18,915
and the nature of the acidosis strongly suggests poisoning.

322
00:24:19,083 --> 00:24:21,960
Now, I don't know what that means, but it sounds bad.

323
00:24:22,128 --> 00:24:23,753
Santiago died at 1 a. m.

324
00:24:23,921 --> 00:24:26,673
At 3, the doctor wasn't able to determine the cause of death.

325
00:24:26,841 --> 00:24:29,050
Two hours later, he said it was poison.

326
00:24:29,218 --> 00:24:31,553
Oh, now I see what you're saying.

327
00:24:31,720 --> 00:24:35,056
It had to be Professor Plum, in the library, with the candlestick.

328
00:24:35,224 --> 00:24:37,559
I'm gonna talk to your supervisor.

329
00:24:37,726 --> 00:24:42,397
Go straight up Pennsylvania Avenue. It's the big white house with the pillars in front.

330
00:24:42,982 --> 00:24:45,316
Thank you. I don't think you'll have much luck.

331
00:24:45,484 --> 00:24:50,238
I was assigned by Division. Somebody over there thinks I'm a pretty good lawyer.

332
00:24:50,406 --> 00:24:56,411
So, while I appreciate your interest and enthusiasm, I think I can handle things.

333
00:24:56,579 --> 00:24:58,580
You know what a Code Red is?

334
00:25:02,751 --> 00:25:04,586
What a pity.

335
00:25:15,014 --> 00:25:17,098
Morning, sir. Morning.

336
00:25:18,100 --> 00:25:20,310
Officer on deck, ten-hut!

337
00:25:20,477 --> 00:25:22,312
Sir! Lance Corporal Harold Dawson, sir!

338
00:25:22,479 --> 00:25:25,064
Rifle Security Company Windward! Second Platoon Bravo!

339
00:25:25,232 --> 00:25:27,692
Someone hasn't been working and playing well with others, Harold.

340
00:25:27,860 --> 00:25:29,777
Sir! Yes, sir!

341
00:25:31,572 --> 00:25:35,158
Sir! PFC Louden Downey, sir!

342
00:25:35,326 --> 00:25:39,120
I'm Daniel Kaffee, this is Sam Weinberg. Sit down.

343
00:25:46,503 --> 00:25:49,047
Is this your signature? Yes, sir.

344
00:25:49,215 --> 00:25:51,132
You don't have to call me sir. Is this your signature?

345
00:25:51,300 --> 00:25:55,470
Sir, yes, sir! Certainly don't need to say it twice.

346
00:25:55,638 --> 00:25:58,932
What's a Code Red? It's a disciplinary engagement.

347
00:25:59,099 --> 00:26:00,475
What's that mean exactly?

348
00:26:00,643 --> 00:26:04,437
Sir, a Marine falls out of line, it's up to the men in his unit to get him on track.

349
00:26:04,730 --> 00:26:07,982
What's a garden-variety Code Red? Sir?

350
00:26:08,150 --> 00:26:14,489
Harold, You say sir and I look for my father. Danny, Daniel Kaffee.

351
00:26:14,657 --> 00:26:17,784
Garden-variety. Typical. What's a basic Code Red?

352
00:26:17,952 --> 00:26:20,411
Sir, a Marine refuses to bathe on a regular basis,

353
00:26:20,579 --> 00:26:23,164
the men in his squad would give him a GI shower.

354
00:26:23,332 --> 00:26:27,085
What's that? Scrub brushes, steel wool.

355
00:26:27,253 --> 00:26:28,503
Beautiful.

356
00:26:28,671 --> 00:26:31,089
Was the attack on Santiago a Code Red?

357
00:26:31,632 --> 00:26:32,840
Yes, sir.

358
00:26:38,264 --> 00:26:41,266
Does he ever talk?

359
00:26:41,433 --> 00:26:44,602
Sir, PFC Downey will answer any direct questions you ask him.

360
00:26:44,770 --> 00:26:46,187
Swell.

361
00:26:48,148 --> 00:26:51,859
Private Downey, the rag you stuffed in Santiago's mouth, was there poison on it?

362
00:26:52,027 --> 00:26:55,238
No, sir. Silver polish, turpentine, antifreeze?

363
00:26:55,406 --> 00:26:57,657
No, sir. We were just gonna shave his head, sir.

364
00:26:57,825 --> 00:27:00,493
When, all of the sudden…

365
00:27:00,995 --> 00:27:03,830
We saw blood dripping down his mouth.

366
00:27:03,998 --> 00:27:07,375
We pulled the tape off and there was blood all down his face, sir.

367
00:27:07,543 --> 00:27:10,586
That's when Lance Corporal Dawson called the ambulance.

368
00:27:10,796 --> 00:27:12,380
Did anyone see you call the ambulance?

369
00:27:14,508 --> 00:27:15,550
No, sir.

370
00:27:18,220 --> 00:27:19,762
Were you there when the ambulance got there?

371
00:27:19,930 --> 00:27:22,265
Yes, that's when we were taken under arrest.

372
00:27:22,433 --> 00:27:28,479
On August 2nd, did you fire a shot across the fenceline, into Cuba?

373
00:27:29,273 --> 00:27:30,481
Yes, sir. Why?

374
00:27:30,649 --> 00:27:33,359
My mirror engaged, sir. His mirror?

375
00:27:33,527 --> 00:27:37,280
For every American sentry, there's a Cuban counterpart. They're called mirrors.

376
00:27:37,448 --> 00:27:40,825
Lance corporal claims his mirror was about to fire at him.

377
00:27:40,993 --> 00:27:46,039
Santiago's letter to the NIS said you fired illegally.

378
00:27:46,206 --> 00:27:51,586
He's saying that the guy, the mirror, he never made a move.

379
00:27:55,382 --> 00:28:00,595
Oh, Harold? You see what I'm getting at?

380
00:28:00,763 --> 00:28:04,265
If Santiago didn't have anything on you, then why did you give him a Code Red?

381
00:28:04,433 --> 00:28:06,476
Because he broke the chain of command, sir.

382
00:28:06,643 --> 00:28:09,729
He what? He went outside of his unit.

383
00:28:09,897 --> 00:28:14,233
If he had a problem, he should have spoken to me, then his sergeant, then…

384
00:28:14,401 --> 00:28:17,904
All right, all right. Did you assault Santiago with the intent of killing him?

385
00:28:18,072 --> 00:28:19,614
No, sir. What was your intent?

386
00:28:19,782 --> 00:28:22,408
To train him, sir. Train him to do what?

387
00:28:22,743 --> 00:28:27,038
To think of his unit before himself. To respect the code.

388
00:28:27,206 --> 00:28:30,958
What's the code? Unit, Corps, God, country!

389
00:28:31,293 --> 00:28:37,256
I beg your pardon? Unit, Corps, God, country, sir.

390
00:28:53,440 --> 00:28:59,487
The government of the United States wants to charge you two with murder.

391
00:28:59,655 --> 00:29:05,076
And you want me to go to the prosecutor with, unit, Corps, God, country?

392
00:29:05,244 --> 00:29:07,161
That's our code, sir.

393
00:29:11,166 --> 00:29:13,000
That's your code. That's your code.

394
00:29:13,168 --> 00:29:15,711
We'll be back.

395
00:29:15,921 --> 00:29:19,632
You guys need anything? Books? Papers? Cigarettes? Ham sandwich?

396
00:29:19,800 --> 00:29:21,926
Sir! No, thank you, sir!

397
00:29:22,386 --> 00:29:25,805
Harold, I think there's a concept you'd better start warming up to.

398
00:29:25,973 --> 00:29:29,809
Sir? I'm the only friend you've got.

399
00:29:43,449 --> 00:29:46,200
Dan Kaffee. Smiling Jack Ross.

400
00:29:46,368 --> 00:29:48,536
Welcome to the big time. You think so?

401
00:29:48,704 --> 00:29:52,457
Let's hope, for Dawson and Downey's sake, you practice law better than you play softball.

402
00:29:52,624 --> 00:29:55,877
Unfortunately for Dawson and Downey, I don't do anything better than I play softball.

403
00:29:56,044 --> 00:29:57,503
- I'm out of here, Jannelle! - Bye.

404
00:29:57,671 --> 00:29:58,921
See you when I get back from Cuba.

405
00:29:59,089 --> 00:30:02,300
Say hi to Castro for me. Will do. What are we looking at?

406
00:30:02,468 --> 00:30:05,553
They plead guilty, we drop conspiracy and conduct unbecoming,

407
00:30:05,721 --> 00:30:07,180
20 years, they're home in half that time.

408
00:30:07,347 --> 00:30:08,473
I want 12. Can't do it.

409
00:30:08,640 --> 00:30:09,932
They called the ambulance, Jack.

410
00:30:10,100 --> 00:30:13,561
I don't care if they called the Avon lady. They killed a Marine.

411
00:30:13,729 --> 00:30:17,857
The rag was tested for poison. The autopsy, lab reports, they all say the same thing: Maybe, maybe not.

412
00:30:18,025 --> 00:30:22,403
The Chief of Internal Medicine at Guantánamo says he's sure.

413
00:30:22,571 --> 00:30:24,280
What do you know about Code Reds?

414
00:30:24,448 --> 00:30:27,617
Oh, man…

415
00:30:28,410 --> 00:30:32,246
Are we off the record? You tell me.

416
00:30:32,414 --> 00:30:34,248
I'm gonna give you the 12 years.

417
00:30:34,416 --> 00:30:37,251
But before you get into trouble tomorrow, I think you should know

418
00:30:37,419 --> 00:30:41,047
the platoon commander, Kendrick, held a meeting with the men

419
00:30:41,215 --> 00:30:45,551
and specifically told them not to touch Santiago.

420
00:30:47,721 --> 00:30:50,598
We still playing hoops tomorrow? Do we have a deal?

421
00:30:51,600 --> 00:30:53,392
I'll talk to you when I get back.

422
00:30:56,813 --> 00:30:58,105
Hi there.

423
00:30:58,273 --> 00:30:59,982
Any luck getting me replaced?

424
00:31:00,150 --> 00:31:02,735
Is there anyone in this command you don't drink or play softball with?

425
00:31:02,903 --> 00:31:04,779
Commander… Listen, I came to make peace.

426
00:31:04,947 --> 00:31:06,447
We got off on the wrong foot.

427
00:31:06,615 --> 00:31:09,075
What do you say, friends? Look, I don't…

428
00:31:09,243 --> 00:31:12,578
I brought Downey some comic books he was asking for.

429
00:31:12,746 --> 00:31:16,624
The kid, Kaffee, I swear, doesn't know where he is. Doesn't even know why he's been arrested.

430
00:31:16,792 --> 00:31:19,794
Commander… JoAnne. You can call me JoAnne. Or Jo.

431
00:31:19,962 --> 00:31:21,254
Jo? Yes.

432
00:31:21,421 --> 00:31:24,382
Jo, if you ever speak to a client of mine again without permission,

433
00:31:24,550 --> 00:31:27,134
I'll have you disbarred. Friends?

434
00:31:27,302 --> 00:31:30,179
I had authorization. From where?

435
00:31:30,347 --> 00:31:35,518
Downey's closest relative, Ginny Miller, his aunt on his mother's side.

436
00:31:35,686 --> 00:31:38,145
You got authorization from Aunt Ginny?

437
00:31:38,313 --> 00:31:42,275
I gave her a call, like you asked. Very nice woman. We spoke for about an hour.

438
00:31:42,442 --> 00:31:45,319
You got authorization from Aunt Ginny.

439
00:31:45,487 --> 00:31:47,697
Perfectly within my province.

440
00:31:47,864 --> 00:31:50,575
Does Aunt Ginny have a barn? We could hold the trial there.

441
00:31:50,742 --> 00:31:54,996
I can sew the costumes, Uncle Goober can be the judge.

442
00:31:57,207 --> 00:32:00,501
I'm going to Cuba with you tomorrow.

443
00:32:01,878 --> 00:32:05,339
And the hits just keep on coming.

444
00:32:27,738 --> 00:32:29,155
How's it going, Luther?

445
00:32:29,323 --> 00:32:31,198
Another day, another dollar.

446
00:32:31,366 --> 00:32:34,368
Gotta play them as they lay. What goes around comes around.

447
00:32:34,536 --> 00:32:37,788
Can't beat them, join them. At least I got my health.

448
00:32:38,206 --> 00:32:41,626
Well, you got everything. See you tomorrow, Luther.

449
00:32:41,793 --> 00:32:44,712
Not if I see you first.

450
00:32:46,048 --> 00:32:50,343
You're my witness. The baby spoke. My daughter said a word.

451
00:32:50,510 --> 00:32:52,887
She made a sound. I'm not sure it was a word.

452
00:32:53,055 --> 00:32:55,890
Come on, now. It was definitely a word.

453
00:32:56,058 --> 00:32:57,433
Okay.

454
00:32:57,643 --> 00:33:02,730
You heard her. She pointed and said Pa. She did.

455
00:33:02,898 --> 00:33:05,608
She was pointing at a mailbox. That's right.

456
00:33:05,776 --> 00:33:09,445
Pointing as if to say, Pa! Look, a mailbox.

457
00:33:16,411 --> 00:33:20,831
Jack Ross offered me the 12 years. That's what you wanted, right?

458
00:33:20,999 --> 00:33:23,250
I know, and I'll…

459
00:33:23,418 --> 00:33:28,631
I mean, I guess I'll take it. I'll take it.

460
00:33:28,799 --> 00:33:30,549
So. .?

461
00:33:30,717 --> 00:33:33,761
It took about 45 seconds. He barely put up a fight.

462
00:33:33,929 --> 00:33:37,765
Danny, take the 12 years, it's a gift.

463
00:33:37,933 --> 00:33:39,767
You don't believe their story, do you?

464
00:33:39,935 --> 00:33:42,103
You think they ought to go to jail for life.

465
00:33:42,270 --> 00:33:44,146
I believe every word of their story,

466
00:33:44,314 --> 00:33:48,192
and I think they ought to go to jail for life.

467
00:33:52,614 --> 00:33:54,782
See you tomorrow. Okay.

468
00:33:54,950 --> 00:33:57,451
Don't forget to wear the whites. Very hot.

469
00:33:57,619 --> 00:33:59,078
I don't like the whites.

470
00:33:59,287 --> 00:34:02,832
Nobody likes the whites, but we're going to Cuba. You got Dramamine?

471
00:34:02,999 --> 00:34:04,291
Dramamine keeps you cool?

472
00:34:04,459 --> 00:34:07,962
No, Dramamine keeps you from throwing up. You get sick when you fly.

473
00:34:08,130 --> 00:34:13,050
I get sick when I fly because I'm afraid of crashing into a large mountain. Dramamine won't help.

474
00:34:14,094 --> 00:34:16,470
I got some oregano, I hear that works pretty good.

475
00:34:19,891 --> 00:34:23,144
Ross said the strangest thing to me right before I left.

476
00:34:23,979 --> 00:34:26,313
He said Lieutenant Kendrick

477
00:34:26,481 --> 00:34:30,317
had told the men specifically not to touch Santiago.

478
00:34:30,736 --> 00:34:33,988
So? I never mentioned Kendrick.

479
00:34:34,156 --> 00:34:36,407
I don't even know who he is.

480
00:34:39,453 --> 00:34:43,164
Ah, what the hell. I'll see you tomorrow.

481
00:35:19,201 --> 00:35:24,330
I'm Corporal Barnes, I'm to escort you to the Windward side of the base.

482
