Probably. What do we do then, sir?

722
00:52:28,103 --> 00:52:33,900
We joined the Marines because we wanted to live by a certain code. And we found it in the Corps.

723
00:52:34,068 --> 00:52:39,405
You're asking us to say we have no honor, that we're not Marines!

724
00:52:39,573 --> 00:52:43,868
If a court decides what we did was wrong, I'll accept my punishment.

725
00:52:44,036 --> 00:52:49,749
But I believe I was right. I did my job. I will not dishonor myself, my unit,

726
00:52:49,917 --> 00:52:55,046
or the Corps, so that I can go home in six months!

727
00:52:55,214 --> 00:52:57,048
Sir!

728
00:53:03,848 --> 00:53:08,434
I'd like to talk to Lance Corporal Dawson alone for a minute, please.

729
00:53:10,104 --> 00:53:11,437
Sergeant!

730
00:53:12,064 --> 00:53:14,399
We're gonna go in another room.

731
00:53:14,567 --> 00:53:19,153
- We'd like to go in another room. - Sit down.

732
00:53:26,662 --> 00:53:28,329
You, uh…

733
00:53:30,875 --> 00:53:32,876
You don't like me very much, do you?

734
00:53:34,378 --> 00:53:38,590
Forget it, don't answer that. It doesn't matter.

735
00:53:43,804 --> 00:53:48,892
You know, Downey worships you.

736
00:53:51,145 --> 00:53:53,563
He's gonna do whatever you do.

737
00:53:54,648 --> 00:53:59,485
Are you really gonna let this happen to him because of a code, Harold?

738
00:53:59,653 --> 00:54:01,821
Do you think we were right? Doesn't matter…

739
00:54:01,989 --> 00:54:03,406
Do you think we were right?!

740
00:54:04,241 --> 00:54:05,992
I think you'd lose.

741
00:54:08,120 --> 00:54:09,704
You're such a coward.

742
00:54:09,872 --> 00:54:12,498
I can't believe they let you wear a uniform.

743
00:54:15,002 --> 00:54:17,754
I'm not gonna feel responsible for this. I did all I could.

744
00:54:17,922 --> 00:54:24,135
You're going to Leavenworth for the better part of your life, and I don't give a shit.

745
00:54:24,303 --> 00:54:28,181
What happened to saluting an officer when he leaves the room?

746
00:54:36,231 --> 00:54:37,357
Open it up.

747
00:54:40,694 --> 00:54:44,614
I don't believe it! He's gonna go to jail just to spite me!

748
00:54:44,782 --> 00:54:47,533
Fine. If he wants to jump off a cliff, that's his business.

749
00:54:47,701 --> 00:54:49,369
I'm not gonna hold his hand.

750
00:54:49,536 --> 00:54:53,915
How do I get him a new lawyer? Make a motion at the arraignment.

751
00:54:54,083 --> 00:54:58,378
Just tell the judge you want new counsel assigned.

752
00:55:00,047 --> 00:55:01,381
That's that.

753
00:55:02,091 --> 00:55:04,717
One thing, though. When you ask the judge for new counsel,

754
00:55:04,885 --> 00:55:06,719
Danny, be sure and ask nicely.

755
00:55:07,596 --> 00:55:08,888
What do you want from me?

756
00:55:09,056 --> 00:55:13,559
I want you to let them be judged. I want you to stand up and make an argument.

757
00:55:13,727 --> 00:55:18,523
That didn't help Calley at My Lai, or the Nazis at Nuremburg.

758
00:55:18,691 --> 00:55:21,901
For chrissakes, Sam. Do you think that's the same

759
00:55:22,069 --> 00:55:25,446
as two teenagers executing an order they didn't think would result in harm?

760
00:55:25,614 --> 00:55:27,490
These guys aren't Nazis.

761
00:55:27,658 --> 00:55:30,576
Don't look now, but you're making an argument.

762
00:55:32,246 --> 00:55:35,873
Yeah, yeah. Tomorrow morning, I get them a new attorney.

763
00:55:36,041 --> 00:55:40,336
Why are you so afraid to be a lawyer? Were Daddy's expectations really that high?

764
00:55:40,504 --> 00:55:43,756
Please, spare me the psychobabble father bullshit!

765
00:55:43,924 --> 00:55:47,427
They'll have their day in court, but with another lawyer.

766
00:55:47,594 --> 00:55:52,056
Another lawyer won't be good enough. They need you. You know how to win.

767
00:55:52,224 --> 00:55:56,602
You know they have a case. You walk away from this, you seal their fate.

768
00:55:56,770 --> 00:56:00,064
Their fate was sealed the moment Santiago died.

769
00:56:00,232 --> 00:56:01,899
Do you believe they have a case?

770
00:56:02,067 --> 00:56:04,944
You and Dawson, you both live in the same dream world.

771
00:56:05,112 --> 00:56:09,157
It doesn't matter what I believe, it only matters what I can prove.

772
00:56:09,324 --> 00:56:13,953
So don't tell me what I know and don't know. I know the law!

773
00:56:19,126 --> 00:56:23,171
You know nothing about the law. You're a used-car salesman.

774
00:56:23,338 --> 00:56:29,552
An ambulance-chaser with a rank. You're nothing. Live with that.

775
00:56:35,684 --> 00:56:37,310
So I told Duncan,

776
00:56:37,478 --> 00:56:41,481
If you wanna take this to court, you'll force me to file discovery motions,

777
00:56:41,648 --> 00:56:45,151
and you're gonna spend a year going blind on paperwork

778
00:56:45,319 --> 00:56:48,488
because a 90-year-old man misread the Delaware insurance code.

779
00:56:48,655 --> 00:56:49,864
So, what happened?

780
00:56:50,032 --> 00:56:53,951
Fifteen minutes later, he makes a deal.

781
00:57:40,124 --> 00:57:42,333
All rise.

782
00:57:49,091 --> 00:57:55,346
Where are we? Docket number 411275 VR-5.

783
00:57:55,514 --> 00:57:58,099
The United States v. Lance Corporal Harold W. Dawson

784
00:57:58,267 --> 00:58:00,476
and Private First Class Louden Downey.

785
00:58:00,644 --> 00:58:03,896
The accused are charged with murder, conspiracy to commit murder,

786
00:58:04,064 --> 00:58:06,315
and conduct unbecoming a United States Marine.

787
00:58:06,483 --> 00:58:08,526
Does the defense wish to enter a plea?

788
00:58:10,279 --> 00:58:11,737
Yeah.

789
00:58:15,492 --> 00:58:16,826
They're not guilty.

790
00:58:20,080 --> 00:58:22,665
Enter a plea of not guilty for the accused.

791
00:58:22,833 --> 00:58:29,589
We will adjourn until 1000, three weeks from today, when we will reconvene.

792
00:58:45,772 --> 00:58:49,066
Why does a lieutenant with nine months' experience

793
00:58:49,234 --> 00:58:53,487
and a track record for plea-bargaining get assigned a murder case?

794
00:58:55,532 --> 00:58:59,785
Would it be so that it never sees the inside of a courtroom?

795
00:59:01,038 --> 00:59:02,830
We'll work out of my apartment every night at 7:00.

796
00:59:02,998 --> 00:59:07,543
Jo, pick up a carton of legal pads, half a dozen boxes of red pens, half a dozen boxes of black pens.

797
00:59:07,711 --> 00:59:11,088
Sam, get a couple desk lamps. I need you to start a medical profile.

798
00:59:11,256 --> 00:59:15,134
Jo, get Dawson's, Downey's and Santiago's conduct reports.

799
00:59:15,302 --> 00:59:19,597
I've only got Yoo-hoo and Cocoa Puffs, so if you want anything else, bring it.

800
00:59:19,765 --> 00:59:21,891
Okay? Yeah.

801
00:59:28,065 --> 00:59:31,234
So this is what a courtroom looks like.

802
00:59:40,869 --> 00:59:43,996
Did you speak to your friend at the NIS?

803
00:59:44,164 --> 00:59:45,164
Yeah.

804
00:59:45,332 --> 00:59:49,669
She said if Markinson doesn't want to be found, we won't find him.

805
00:59:49,836 --> 00:59:52,630
She said I could be Markinson, and you wouldn't know it.

806
00:59:54,258 --> 00:59:58,594
Are you Markinson? No.

807
00:59:58,804 --> 01:00:03,683
I'm not Markinson. That's two down.

808
01:00:05,769 --> 01:00:07,770
What?

809
01:00:08,438 --> 01:00:11,941
I'm just wondering, now that JoAnne's on this…

810
01:00:12,442 --> 01:00:14,819
I'm just wondering if you still need me.

811
01:00:14,987 --> 01:00:17,530
They were following orders, Sam. An illegal order.

812
01:00:17,698 --> 01:00:19,991
You think Dawson and Downey knew it was illegal?

813
01:00:20,242 --> 01:00:22,827
It doesn't matter. Any decent human would have…

814
01:00:22,995 --> 01:00:25,705
They're not permitted to question orders.

815
01:00:25,872 --> 01:00:30,501
Then what's the secret? I give orders every day, nobody obeys!

816
01:00:30,669 --> 01:00:32,378
We have softball and marching bands.

817
01:00:32,546 --> 01:00:36,799
They work at a place where you have to wear camouflage or you might get shot.

818
01:00:44,516 --> 01:00:48,769
I need you. You're better at research than I am.

819
01:00:48,937 --> 01:00:51,564
And you know how to prepare a witness.

820
01:00:56,987 --> 01:01:01,741
I've got medical reports and Chinese food. I say we eat first.

821
01:01:07,539 --> 01:01:08,664
What?

822
01:01:10,876 --> 01:01:13,711
Did you get any kung pao chicken?

823
01:01:16,340 --> 01:01:19,425
This is our defense. Intent. No one can prove there was poison on the rag.

824
01:01:19,593 --> 01:01:22,720
Code Red. They're common and accepted in Guantánamo Bay.

825
01:01:22,888 --> 01:01:28,351
The order. A, Kendrick gave it, B, they had no choice but to follow. That's it.

826
01:01:28,518 --> 01:01:30,895
- What about motive? - We're weak. They had one.

827
01:01:31,063 --> 01:01:33,105
That doesn't make them guilty.

828
01:01:33,273 --> 01:01:36,776
Relax. We'll deal with that later. For now, we start with intent.

829
01:01:36,943 --> 01:01:41,906
We must show that Santiago could have died from something other than poison.

830
01:01:42,074 --> 01:01:46,452
Jo, find out everything about lactic acidosis.

831
01:01:46,620 --> 01:01:49,163
This is Lieutenant Commander Galloway with the JAG Corps.

832
01:01:49,331 --> 01:01:53,125
I've been trying to track down a Lieutenant Colonel Matthew Markinson…

833
01:01:53,293 --> 01:01:54,752
Doctor, was there any sign of external damage?

834
01:01:54,920 --> 01:01:57,296
No. No scrapes? No cuts?

835
01:01:57,464 --> 01:02:00,466
No. No. Bruises? Broken bones?

836
01:02:00,634 --> 01:02:02,635
Was there any sign of violence?

837
01:02:02,803 --> 01:02:07,473
Other than the dead body? Shit. I walk into that every time.

838
01:02:07,641 --> 01:02:12,186
He ordered me and Dawson to give Willy a Code Red.

839
01:02:12,354 --> 01:02:13,979
Answers still have to come faster.

840
01:02:14,147 --> 01:02:16,148
This Iowa farm boy thing will play for a while,

841
01:02:16,316 --> 01:02:18,901
but in the end, it sounds like he's searching for the truth.

842
01:02:19,069 --> 01:02:20,986
He's right. And Willy is Private Santiago.

843
01:02:21,154 --> 01:02:25,491
You start calling him Willy and all the sudden he's a person who's got a mother who's gonna miss him.

844
01:02:26,493 --> 01:02:27,785
They drew court members.

845
01:02:27,953 --> 01:02:30,121
Seven men, two women. Five Navy, four Marines.

846
01:02:30,288 --> 01:02:32,248
All experienced officers.

847
01:02:32,416 --> 01:02:35,334
The women have no children. That's a bad break.

848
01:02:35,502 --> 01:02:39,547
My father said a jury trial is about assigning blame.

849
01:02:39,714 --> 01:02:44,218
Santiago's dead and he shouldn't be. They want to know who's to blame.

850
01:02:44,386 --> 01:02:46,804
Ross hands them our clients, we hand them Kendrick.

851
01:02:46,972 --> 01:02:52,560
This won't be won by the law, but by the lawyers. So, poker faces.

852
01:02:52,727 --> 01:02:57,940
Don't flinch. If something goes wrong, don't hang your head or scribble.

853
01:02:58,108 --> 01:03:01,777
Whatever happens, you have to look like you expected it.

854
01:03:01,945 --> 01:03:03,154
You pass me documents…

855
01:03:03,321 --> 01:03:06,740
Swiftly, and don't look overanxious.

856
01:03:06,908 --> 01:03:09,618
Don't wear that perfume in court, it wrecks my concentration.

857
01:03:09,786 --> 01:03:13,414
Really? I was talking to Sam.

858
01:03:14,749 --> 01:03:18,294
What time is it? It's time to go home. Try to sleep.

859
01:03:18,837 --> 01:03:20,212
Yeah. Give me a ride?

860
01:03:20,380 --> 01:03:22,214
Sure.

861
01:03:25,427 --> 01:03:26,969
You're a good man, Charlie Brown.

862
01:03:27,137 --> 01:03:31,223
I'll see you in court, counselor.

863
01:03:36,438 --> 01:03:39,899
Danny, I… I know. We've had our differences.

864
01:03:40,066 --> 01:03:44,778
We both said things we didn't mean. But you're happy I stuck with the case.

865
01:03:44,946 --> 01:03:51,076
If you've gained some respect for me, well, of course I'm happy about that.

866
01:03:51,244 --> 01:03:55,581
But it's no big deal. You like me, I won't make you say it.

867
01:03:56,374 --> 01:03:59,084
I was just gonna tell you to wear matching socks tomorrow.

868
01:04:00,795 --> 01:04:04,340
Okay. Good tip.

869
01:04:05,133 --> 01:04:08,886
We're ready. Better believe it.

870
01:04:19,022 --> 01:04:22,024
We're gonna get creamed.

871
01:04:50,095 --> 01:04:52,012
Lieutenant Kaffee.

872
01:04:52,847 --> 01:04:55,891
You are gonna save our son, aren't you?

873
01:04:56,059 --> 01:04:58,060
I'll do my best.

874
01:04:58,228 --> 01:05:02,648
Danny, I'd like you to meet Ginny Miller, Louden's aunt.

875
01:05:03,525 --> 01:05:06,110
You're Aunt Ginny? Uh-huh.

876
01:05:07,821 --> 01:05:12,783
I was expecting someone older. So was I.

877
01:05:17,497 --> 01:05:20,165
- Last chance. I'll flip you for it. - All rise.

878
01:05:20,333 --> 01:05:21,333
Too late.

879
01:05:30,010 --> 01:05:35,764
All those having business with this general court-martial, stand forward.

880
01:05:35,932 --> 01:05:39,268
Colonel Julius Alexander Randolph is presiding.

881
01:05:39,436 --> 01:05:41,854
Is the government prepared to make an opening statement?

882
01:05:42,022 --> 01:05:43,522
Yes, sir.

883
01:05:46,610 --> 01:05:48,485
The facts of the case are these:

884
01:05:48,653 --> 01:05:54,700
On September 6th, the accused entered PFC Santiago's room.

885
01:05:54,868 --> 01:05:57,703
They woke him up, tied his arms and legs,

886
01:05:57,871 --> 01:06:00,205
and forced a rag into his throat.

887
01:06:00,373 --> 01:06:06,045
Minutes later, a reaction called lactic acidosis caused his lungs to bleed.

888
01:06:06,212 --> 01:06:11,717
He drowned in his own blood, and was dead at 37 minutes past midnight.

889
01:06:11,885 --> 01:06:16,889
These are the facts of the case, and they are undisputed.

890
01:06:17,057 --> 01:06:22,353
That's right. What I've just told you is exactly what you will hear

891
01:06:22,520 --> 01:06:27,107
from Lance Corporal Dawson and Private Downey.

892
01:06:27,275 --> 01:06:32,321
Furthermore, we will also show that the accused soaked the rag in poison

893
01:06:32,489 --> 01:06:36,408
and entered Santiago's room with motive and intent to kill.

894
01:06:37,702 --> 01:06:43,040
Lieutenant Kaffee is gonna try and pull off a little magic act here.

895
01:06:43,208 --> 01:06:45,584
He's gonna try a little misdirection.

896
01:06:46,044 --> 01:06:49,296
He'll astonish you with stories of rituals.

897
01:06:49,464 --> 01:06:55,678
Dazzle you with official-sounding terms like Code Red.

898
01:06:55,845 --> 01:06:58,806
He might even try to cut into a few officers for you.

899
01:06:58,973 --> 01:07:03,727
He'll have no evidence, none, but it'll be entertaining.

900
01:07:03,978 --> 01:07:05,396
When we get to the end,

901
01:07:05,563 --> 01:07:10,150
all the magic in the world will not divert your attention from the fact

902
01:07:10,318 --> 01:07:17,241
that Willy Santiago is dead, and Dawson and Downey killed him.

903
01:07:17,409 --> 01:07:21,245
These are the facts of the case, and they are undisputed.

904
01:07:22,372 --> 01:07:24,081
Lieutenant Kaffee.

905
01:07:24,249 --> 01:07:27,251
There was no poison on the rag and there was no intent to kill,

906
01:07:27,419 --> 01:07:31,463
and any attempt to prove otherwise is futile, because it just ain't true.

907
01:07:32,048 --> 01:07:37,678
Dawson and Downey didn't go into Santiago's room because of vengeance or hatred.

908
01:07:37,887 --> 01:07:41,849
It wasn't to kill or harm. And they weren't looking for kicks.

909
01:07:42,016 --> 01:07:45,310
It's because it was what they were ordered to do.

910
01:07:45,895 --> 01:07:50,482
Let me say that again. It's because it was what they were ordered to do.

911
01:07:51,109 --> 01:07:52,985
Out in the real world, that means nothing.

912
01:07:53,153 --> 01:07:55,487
And here in the Washington Navy Yard,

913
01:07:55,655 --> 01:07:57,281
doesn't mean a whole lot more.

914
01:07:57,449 --> 01:07:58,991
But if you're a Marine,

915
01:07:59,159 --> 01:08:03,454
assigned to Rifle Security Company Windward, Guantánamo Bay, Cuba,

916
01:08:03,621 --> 01:08:06,999
you follow orders, or you pack your bags.

917
01:08:07,208 --> 01:08:12,421
Make no mistake about it. Dawson and Downey are sitting here

918
01:08:12,589 --> 01:08:15,841
because they did their job.

919
01:08:19,429 --> 01:08:22,514
Is the government ready to call its first witness?

920
01:08:22,682 --> 01:08:26,351
Please the court, government calls Mr. R.C. McGuire.

921
01:08:30,857 --> 01:08:33,025
Raise your right hand, please.

922
01:08:33,193 --> 01:08:38,864
Do you swear to tell the truth, the whole truth, and nothing but the truth?

923
01:08:39,032 --> 01:08:41,408
- McGUIRE: I do. - Have a seat, please.

924
01:08:42,494 --> 01:08:45,704
Would you state your full name and occupation?

925
01:08:45,872 --> 01:08:48,874
Robert C. McGuire, special agent, Naval Investigative Service.

926
01:08:49,042 --> 01:08:50,209
Thank you.

927
01:08:50,376 --> 01:08:56,715
Did you receive a letter from PFC Santiago on 3 September of this year?

928
01:08:56,883 --> 01:08:58,967
We did. What did it say?

929
01:08:59,135 --> 01:09:03,847
That a member of Santiago's unit had illegally fired across the fenceline.

930
01:09:04,015 --> 01:09:06,058
Was that Marine identified in the letter?

931
01:09:06,226 --> 01:09:11,730
No. I told Colonel Jessep that I would be coming down to investigate.

932
01:09:11,898 --> 01:09:13,565
And what did you find?

933
01:09:13,733 --> 01:09:18,529
The shift reported only one sentry returned his weapon with ammo missing.

934
01:09:18,696 --> 01:09:21,990
Who was that? Lance Corporal Harold Dawson.

935
01:09:22,158 --> 01:09:23,742
Your Witness.

936
01:09:26,329 --> 01:09:29,665
Mr. McGuire, have you questioned Dawson about the shooting?

937
01:09:29,916 --> 01:09:33,544
Yes, he claims to have been engaged in some manner by the enemy.

938
01:09:33,711 --> 01:09:35,963
But you don't believe him? It's not my place…

939
01:09:36,130 --> 01:09:41,009
Why wasn't Dawson charged with firing at the enemy without cause?

940
01:09:42,804 --> 01:09:45,681
There wasn't enough evidence to support such a charge.

941
01:09:45,849 --> 01:09:47,474
Thank you.

942
01:09:48,893 --> 01:09:53,188
Why was there not enough evidence?

943
01:09:53,356 --> 01:09:55,941
You had William Santiago's letter.

944
01:09:57,110 --> 01:10:02,614
Santiago was the only eyewitness. I had no chance to interview him.

945
01:10:02,782 --> 01:10:05,784
And now we'll never know, will we, Mr. McGuire?

946
01:10:06,536 --> 01:10:07,995
No.

947
01:10:09,414 --> 01:10:13,584
No more questions. The witness is excused.

948
01:10:16,504 --> 01:10:18,964
Corporal Carl Hammaker, Marine barracks,

949
01:10:19,132 --> 01:10:22,467
Rifle Security Company Windward, 2nd Platoon Bravo.

950
01:10:22,635 --> 01:10:29,433
Were you present at a meeting held by Lieutenant Kendrick on September 6th?

951
01:10:29,601 --> 01:10:33,478
Yes, sir. What was the substance of it?

952
01:10:33,646 --> 01:10:36,690
Lieutenant Kendrick told us we had an informer in our group.

953
01:10:36,858 --> 01:10:42,487
That Santiago had reported to the NIS on a member of our platoon.

954
01:10:42,655 --> 01:10:44,865
Did that make you mad?

955
01:10:45,033 --> 01:10:48,327
You can tell the truth. Did it? Yes, sir.

956
01:10:48,494 --> 01:10:49,661
How mad?

957
01:10:49,829 --> 01:10:53,582
Santiago betrayed a code we believe in very deeply.

958
01:10:53,750 --> 01:10:56,376
Were other men also angry? Object. Speculation.

959
01:10:56,628 --> 01:10:58,211
Were Dawson and Downey?

960
01:10:58,463 --> 01:11:00,714
Is the counsel asking this witness to testify

961
01:11:00,882 --> 01:11:03,508
as to how my clients felt on Sept. 6th?

962
01:11:03,927 --> 01:11:05,510
Sustained.

963
01:11:07,388 --> 01:11:11,350
Did Lieutenant Kendrick leave a standing order at that meeting?

964
01:11:11,517 --> 01:11:13,769
Yes, sir. What was it?

965
01:11:15,897 --> 01:11:19,316
It was clear he didn't want us taking matters into our own hands.

966
01:11:19,484 --> 01:11:26,198
What was the order? Santiago wasn't to be touched.

967
01:11:27,617 --> 01:11:30,452
Your witness.

968
01:11:30,620 --> 01:11:34,373
Were you in Dawson and Downey's room five minutes later?

969
01:11:34,540 --> 01:11:35,874
No, sir.

970
01:11:36,250 --> 01:11:40,879
Thanks. No more questions. The witness is excused.

971
01:11:44,842 --> 01:11:47,260
Government calls Corporal Raymond Thomas.

972
01:11:47,428 --> 01:11:52,933
Please the court, I understand Captain Ross is planning to call all the members of the platoon to testify.

973
01:11:53,101 --> 01:11:55,477
In light of the defense Kaffee is planning,

974
01:11:55,645 --> 01:11:59,314
the platoon leader's instructions seems relevant testimony.

975
01:11:59,482 --> 01:12:04,069
The defense concedes that all 22 will confirm Hammaker's account

976
01:12:04,237 --> 01:12:06,488
if the government concedes none of them

977
01:12:06,656 --> 01:12:10,409
were in Dawson and Downey's room at 1620.

978
01:12:10,576 --> 01:12:14,913
Captain? The government will stipulate.

979
01:12:15,081 --> 01:12:19,001
Then we will adjourn. You can call your next witness tomorrow.

980
01:12:19,168 --> 01:12:20,919
All rise.

981
01:12:32,598 --> 01:12:35,308
Let's go over the doctor again. It's the right approach.

982
01:12:35,560 --> 01:12:37,352
We've been over this already.

983
01:12:37,520 --> 01:12:41,231
At 3:00, Stone says he doesn't know what killed Santiago.

984
01:12:41,399 --> 01:12:46,111
Then he meets with Jessep, and at 5:00 he says it was poison? He's not telling the truth.

985
01:12:46,279 --> 01:12:47,362
Oh, that's a relief.

986
01:12:47,530 --> 01:12:50,991
I was afraid I couldn't use the liar, liar, pants on fire defense.

987
01:12:51,159 --> 01:12:57,414
We can't prove coercion. Let's go over what we have.

988
01:13:06,049 --> 01:13:09,634
Private Santiago was admitted to the ER at 0012,

989
01:13:09,802 --> 01:13:13,680
and he was pronounced dead at 0037.

990
01:13:13,848 --> 01:13:17,142
Dr. Stone, what is lactic acidosis?

991
01:13:17,310 --> 01:13:20,896
If the muscles and other cells burn sugar instead of oxygen,

992
01:13:21,064 --> 01:13:22,564
lactic acid is produced.

993
01:13:22,732 --> 01:13:26,151
That lactic acid is what caused Santiago's lungs to bleed.

994
01:13:26,319 --> 01:13:31,656
How long does it take before the muscles start burning sugar?

995
01:13:32,533 --> 01:13:38,121
Twenty to 30 minutes. What made it faster with Santiago?

996
01:13:38,289 --> 01:13:43,502
An ingested poison of some kind. Object. The witness is speculating.

997
01:13:43,669 --> 01:13:45,378
He is an expert medical witness.

998
01:13:45,546 --> 01:13:48,173
In this court, his opinion is not speculation.

999
01:13:48,341 --> 01:13:53,845
He is not a criminologist. The medical facts are inconclusive.

1000
01:13:54,013 --> 01:13:57,682
A point I'm confident you'll illustrate on your cross-examination.

1001
01:13:57,850 --> 01:14:00,852
So I'm sure you won't mind if his opinion is admitted now?

1002
01:14:01,437 --> 01:14:03,522
Not at all, sir.

1003
01:14:05,066 --> 01:14:11,154
Did Willy Santiago die of poisoning? Absolutely.

1004
01:14:11,322 --> 01:14:15,325
You're aware that the lab and coroner's reports show no traces of poison?

1005
01:14:15,493 --> 01:14:17,953
Yes, I am. Then how do you justify…?

1006
01:14:18,121 --> 01:14:21,039
There are literally dozens of toxins which are virtually undetectable,

1007
01:14:21,207 --> 01:14:23,583
both in the human body and on the fabric.

1008
01:14:23,751 --> 01:14:27,462
The nature of the acidosis is the compelling factor here.

1009
01:14:28,047 --> 01:14:30,173
Thank you, sir.

1010
01:14:32,260 --> 01:14:36,888
Commander, is it possible for a person to have an affliction, some condition,

1011
01:14:37,056 --> 01:14:39,891
which might also speed up acidosis?

1012
01:14:42,728 --> 01:14:46,481
Is it possible? It's possible.

1013
01:14:46,649 --> 01:14:50,110
What might some of those conditions be?

1014
01:14:50,278 --> 01:14:53,405
If a person had a coronary or cerebral disorder,

1015
01:14:53,573 --> 01:14:55,657
the process would be more rapid.

1016
01:14:55,825 --> 01:14:57,909
If I had a coronary condition

1017
01:14:58,077 --> 01:15:01,663
and a perfectly clean rag was placed in my mouth and pushed too far,

1018
01:15:01,831 --> 01:15:04,749
is it possible my cells would continue burning sugar

1019
01:15:04,917 --> 01:15:06,418
after the rag was taken out?

1020
01:15:06,919 --> 01:15:09,379
It would have to be a very serious condition.

1021
01:15:09,547 --> 01:15:13,800
Is it possible to have a serious condition where initial symptoms were so mild

1022
01:15:13,968 --> 01:15:18,221
as to escape a physician during a routine medical exam?

1023
01:15:18,389 --> 01:15:21,099
Possibly. There would still be symptoms.

1024
01:15:21,267 --> 01:15:22,601
What kind of symptoms?

1025
01:15:23,019 --> 01:15:25,228
There are hundreds of… Chest pains?

1026
01:15:25,396 --> 01:15:28,607
Yes. Yes. Shortness of breath? Fatigue?

1027
01:15:29,066 --> 01:15:30,442
Of course.

1028
01:15:36,240 --> 01:15:40,744
Doctor, is this your signature? Yes, it is.

1029
01:15:41,287 --> 01:15:45,123
This is an order for Private Santiago to be put on restricted duty.

1030
01:15:45,291 --> 01:15:49,127
Would you read your handwritten remarks at the bottom of the page?

1031
01:15:49,295 --> 01:15:55,634
Patient complains of chest pains, shortness of breath, and fatigue.

1032
01:15:55,801 --> 01:16:00,138
Restricted from running distances over five miles for one week.

1033
01:16:02,308 --> 01:16:05,644
Isn't it possible Santiago had a serious coronary condition

1034
01:16:05,811 --> 01:16:10,815
and it was that condition, not poison, that caused the rapid chemical reaction?

1035
01:16:10,983 --> 01:16:14,152
No. It's not possible?

1036
01:16:14,654 --> 01:16:19,157
No. I personally give each man a thorough physical examination.

1037
01:16:19,325 --> 01:16:22,327
Private Santiago was given a clean bill of health.

1038
01:16:22,495 --> 01:16:24,829
That's why it had to be poison, right?

1039
01:16:24,997 --> 01:16:27,791
Because if you gave a man with a serious condition

1040
01:16:27,959 --> 01:16:31,670
a clean bill of health and he died from a heart-related incident,

1041
01:16:31,837 --> 01:16:33,755
you'd have a lot to answer for.

1042
01:16:33,923 --> 01:16:36,800
- Object! Move to strike! - Sustained.

1043
01:16:38,052 --> 01:16:41,179
I have no more questions, Your Honor.

1044
01:16:41,347 --> 01:16:44,683
You've held a license to practice medicine for 17 years.

1045
01:16:44,850 --> 01:16:48,478
You're certified in internal medicine, you're chief of internal medicine

1046
01:16:48,646 --> 01:16:52,691
at a hospital which has served 5426 people.

1047
01:16:52,858 --> 01:16:57,654
In your professional opinion, was Willy Santiago poisoned?

1048
01:16:57,822 --> 01:17:02,575
We ask that the doctor's testimony be stricken from the record.

1049
01:17:02,743 --> 01:17:06,663
The court members should lend no weight to this witness's testimony.

1050
01:17:06,831 --> 01:17:08,373
The objection's overruled.

1051
01:17:08,541 --> 01:17:13,420
We strenuously object, and requests an 802 conference

1052
01:17:13,587 --> 01:17:16,798
so His Honor can hear discussion before ruling on this objection.

1053
01:17:16,966 --> 01:17:21,636
The objection has been overruled. Move to reconsider.

1054
01:17:21,804 --> 01:17:27,058
Noted. The witness is an expert, and the court will hear his opinion!

1055
01:17:31,480 --> 01:17:36,234
In your expert professional opinion,

1056
01:17:36,402 --> 01:17:39,029
was Willy Santiago poisoned?

1057
01:17:39,989 --> 01:17:44,868
Yes. Thank you, sir. No more questions.

1058
01:17:45,119 --> 01:17:47,370
You may step down.

1059
01:17:51,083 --> 01:17:57,380
While we reserve the right to call rebuttal witnesses, government rests.

1060
01:17:57,548 --> 01:18:00,050
We'll recess until Monday the 19th,

1061
01:18:00,217 --> 01:18:03,595
when the defense will call its first witness.

1062
01:18:05,139 --> 01:18:07,265
All rise.

1063
01:18:15,816 --> 01:18:21,071
I strenuously object? Is that how it works?

1064
01:18:21,238 --> 01:18:25,283
Objection. Overruled! No, I strenuously object!

1065
01:18:25,451 --> 01:18:29,454
Oh, then I'll reconsider! I got it on the record.

1066
01:18:29,622 --> 01:18:32,082
You got the court thinking we're afraid of the doctor.

1067
01:18:32,249 --> 01:18:34,793
You object once, so we can say he's not a criminologist.

1068
01:18:35,002 --> 01:18:38,296
You keep after it, our cross looks like a bunch of fancy lawyer tricks.

1069
01:18:38,547 --> 01:18:41,716
It's the difference between paper law and trial law!

1070
01:18:41,967 --> 01:18:45,387
The judge called him an expert! Sam, she made a mistake.

1071
01:18:45,554 --> 01:18:47,222
Let's not relive it.

1072
01:18:48,974 --> 01:18:53,436
I'm gonna go call my wife. I'll see you tonight.

1073
01:18:54,814 --> 01:18:59,401
Why do you hate them so much? They beat up on a weakling.

1074
01:18:59,568 --> 01:19:02,654
The rest is this just smoke-filled-coffeehouse crap.

1075
01:19:02,822 --> 01:19:05,907
They tortured and tormented a weaker kid!

1076
01:19:06,075 --> 01:19:10,954
They didn't like him, so they killed him. Why? Because he couldn't run very fast!

1077
01:19:11,122 --> 01:19:14,666
Everybody take the night off.

1078
01:19:14,834 --> 01:19:16,668
I'm sorry…

1079
01:19:16,836 --> 01:19:23,007
We've been working 20 hours a day. Go see your wife and daughter.

1080
01:19:23,175 --> 01:19:25,176
Jo, go do…

1081
01:19:26,429 --> 01:19:30,181
Whatever it is you do when you're not here.

1082
01:19:30,433 --> 01:19:32,767
What day is tomorrow? Saturday.

1083
01:19:32,935 --> 01:19:34,936
We'll start at 10.

1084
01:19:38,941 --> 01:19:42,026
Why do you like them so much?

1085
01:19:45,489 --> 01:19:49,617
Because they stand on a wall and say, Nothing's gonna hurt you tonight.

1086
01:19:49,785 --> 01:19:51,661
Not on my watch.

1087
01:19:56,750 --> 01:19:59,878
Don't worry about the doctor. This trial starts Monday.

1088
01:20:28,782 --> 01:20:32,076
I'm sorry to bother you. I should have called first.

1089
01:20:32,244 --> 01:20:37,624
No, I was just watching the ball game. Come on in.

1090
01:20:51,347 --> 01:20:56,893
I was wondering how you'd feel if I took you to dinner tonight?

1091
01:20:57,061 --> 01:20:59,938
Are you asking me out on a date? No.

1092
01:21:00,105 --> 01:21:02,065
It sounded like you were. I wasn't.

1093
01:21:02,233 --> 01:21:05,109
I've been asked out before, and that's what it sounded like.

1094
01:21:06,237 --> 01:21:09,280
Do you like seafood? I know a good seafood place.

1095
01:21:09,448 --> 01:21:10,949
Okay.

1096
01:21:17,456 --> 01:21:20,625
My third case was a drunk and disorderly. It lasted nine weeks.

1097
01:21:20,793 --> 01:21:23,461
I rounded up 31 people from the bar that night.

1098
01:21:23,629 --> 01:21:26,965
Nine weeks on a D and D? What was the prosecutor offering?

1099
01:21:27,132 --> 01:21:29,592
Fifteen days.

1100
01:21:31,428 --> 01:21:33,429
You sure hustled the shit out of him.

1101
01:21:33,597 --> 01:21:35,723
After that, they moved me to Internal Affairs.

1102
01:21:35,891 --> 01:21:36,891
Tough to blame them.

1103
01:21:37,059 --> 01:21:41,729
Where I have earned two medals and two letters of commendation.

1104
01:21:42,147 --> 01:21:44,816
Why are you always giving me your résumé?

1105
01:21:48,821 --> 01:21:52,740
I want you to think I'm a good lawyer. I do.

1106
01:21:52,992 --> 01:21:54,993
No, you don't.

1107
01:21:58,539 --> 01:22:00,665
I think you're an exceptional lawyer.

1108
01:22:01,417 --> 01:22:06,129
I watch the court members. They respond to you. They like you.

1109
01:22:06,297 --> 01:22:11,509
I see you convincing them. Dawson and Downey are gonna end up owing their lives to you.

1110
01:22:15,222 --> 01:22:17,890
Jo, I think…

1111
01:22:18,809 --> 01:22:22,478
I think you should prepare yourself for the fact that we're gonna lose.

1112
01:22:22,688 --> 01:22:26,024
Ross's opening statement, it was all true.

1113
01:22:26,191 --> 01:22:30,945
Let's pretend it would matter to the court that the guys were given an order.

1114
01:22:31,113 --> 01:22:33,615
I can't prove it ever happened.

1115
01:22:33,782 --> 01:22:36,284
We'll keep doing what we're doing and put on a show,

1116
01:22:36,452 --> 01:22:41,664
but all we have is the testimony of two people accused of murder.

1117
01:22:42,916 --> 01:22:49,339
We'll find Markinson. Jo, we're gonna lose, and lose huge.

1118
01:22:52,801 --> 01:22:57,889
Corporal Barnes, Windward Barracks, Guantánamo Bay, Cuba.

1119
01:22:58,057 --> 01:23:02,352
Name some reasons why a Marine would receive a Code Red.

1120
01:23:02,519 --> 01:23:05,688
Being late for platoon or company meetings,

1121
01:23:05,856 --> 01:23:09,817
keeping barracks in disorder, falling back on a run…

1122
01:23:09,985 --> 01:23:12,362
Have you ever received a Code Red? Yes, sir.

1123
01:23:12,529 --> 01:23:15,990
We were doing seven-man assault drills, and my weapon slipped.

1124
01:23:16,158 --> 01:23:23,081
It was over 100 degrees. My palms were sweaty and I hadn't used resin like we were taught.

1125
01:23:23,248 --> 01:23:28,002
What happened? The guys threw a blanket over me.

1126
01:23:28,170 --> 01:23:33,466
They punched me on the arms and poured glue on my hands.

1127
01:23:33,634 --> 01:23:37,261
And it worked. I ain't never dropped my weapon since.

1128
01:23:38,847 --> 01:23:42,517
Was Private Santiago ever late? Yes, sir.

1129
01:23:42,685 --> 01:23:45,395
Was his barracks ever in disorder? Yes, sir.

1130
01:23:45,562 --> 01:23:47,980
Did he ever fall back on a run? All the time, sir.

1131
01:23:48,148 --> 01:23:53,277
Did he ever, prior to September 6th, receive a Code Red?

1132
01:23:53,445 --> 01:23:54,737
No, sir.

1133
01:23:54,947 --> 01:23:56,864
Never? No, sir.

1134
01:23:58,492 --> 01:24:00,952
You got a Code Red because your palms were sweaty.

1135
01:24:01,120 --> 01:24:04,789
Why didn't Santiago, this burden to his unit, ever get one?

1136
01:24:06,625 --> 01:24:11,713
Dawson wouldn't allow it, sir. Dawson wouldn't allow it.

1137
01:24:11,880 --> 01:24:17,468
The guys talked tough about Santiago, but they were too afraid of Dawson.

1138
01:24:17,636 --> 01:24:19,971
Object. Witness is speculating.

1139
01:24:20,139 --> 01:24:23,307
I'll rephrase. Did you want to give Santiago a Code Red?

1140
01:24:23,475 --> 01:24:24,559
Yes, sir.

1141
01:24:24,727 --> 01:24:28,646
Why didn't you? Because Dawson would kick my butt.

1142
01:24:28,814 --> 01:24:34,110
Good enough. Captain Ross is gonna ask you some questions.

1143
01:24:34,278 --> 01:24:39,615
Corporal Barnes, I hold here the Marine Outline for Recruit Training.

1144
01:24:39,783 --> 01:24:41,325
Are you familiar with this book? Yes, sir.

1145
01:24:41,493 --> 01:24:43,494
Have you read it? Good. Yes, sir.

1146
01:24:43,662 --> 01:24:47,832
Turn to the chapter that deals with Code Reds, please.

1147
01:24:48,333 --> 01:24:49,333
Sir?

1148
01:24:49,501 --> 01:24:53,004
Just flip to the page that discusses Code Reds.

1149
01:24:55,090 --> 01:25:00,511
Well, Code Red is a term that we use down at Gitmo. I don't know if it's…

1150
01:25:00,679 --> 01:25:02,930
Oh, we're in luck, then.

1151
01:25:06,101 --> 01:25:08,770
Standard Operating Procedure, Rifle Security Company,

1152
01:25:08,937 --> 01:25:10,605
Guantánamo Bay, Cuba.

1153
01:25:10,773 --> 01:25:14,484
I assume we'll find Code Red in there?

1154
01:25:14,651 --> 01:25:16,444
No, sir. No?

1155
01:25:16,612 --> 01:25:22,617
I'm a Marine. Is there no book, no set of orders or regulations,

1156
01:25:22,785 --> 01:25:27,121
telling me that one of my duties is to perform Code Reds?

1157
01:25:27,956 --> 01:25:30,625
No, sir. No book, sir.

1158
01:25:30,793 --> 01:25:33,461
No further questions.

1159
01:25:34,880 --> 01:25:39,717
Would you turn to the page that says where the mess hall is, please?

1160
01:25:39,885 --> 01:25:42,887
Lieutenant Kaffee, that's not in the book, sir.

1161
01:25:44,556 --> 01:25:50,603
You mean you've never had a meal? No, sir. Three squares a day, sir.

1162
01:25:51,396 --> 01:25:56,150
I don't understand. How did you find the mess hall if it's not in this book?

1163
01:25:58,779 --> 01:26:01,864
I guess I just followed the crowd at chow time, sir.

1164
01:26:02,741 --> 01:26:05,076
No more questions.

1165
01:26:05,244 --> 01:26:07,578
Corporal Barnes, you may step down.

1166
01:26:07,746 --> 01:26:08,830
Thank you, sir.

1167
01:26:14,503 --> 01:26:17,129
Seven tonight, we'll do a final Kendrick review.

1168
01:26:17,297 --> 01:26:19,882
I wanna slam-dunk this guy.

1169
01:26:31,270 --> 01:26:32,562
Hey, Luther.

1170
01:26:32,729 --> 01:26:35,731
Admiral! How's the big case going?

1171
01:26:35,899 --> 01:26:38,484
Nose to the grindstone. No flies on you.

1172
01:26:38,735 --> 01:26:40,570
Rolling stone gathers no moss.

1173
01:26:40,821 --> 01:26:43,489
Well, it ain't over till the fat lady sings.

1174
01:26:43,657 --> 01:26:45,616
You can say that again.

1175
01:26:46,201 --> 01:26:49,954
It ain't over till the fat lady sings. Till the fat lady sings.

1176
01:26:50,122 --> 01:26:52,290
I walked into that one.

1177
01:27:03,886 --> 01:27:09,307
Jesus Christ! You left the door unlocked.

1178
01:27:09,474 --> 01:27:12,268
You scared the shit out of me. Just keep driving.

1179
01:27:12,519 --> 01:27:14,312
Are you aware you're under subpoena?

1180
01:27:14,479 --> 01:27:18,190
Yes. I'm also aware the lives of two Marines are in your hands.

1181
01:27:18,358 --> 01:27:20,484
If I could do something about that, I would.

1182
01:27:20,652 --> 01:27:22,778
Since I can't, all I can do is help you.

1183
01:27:22,946 --> 01:27:25,239
What do you know? I know everything.

1184
01:27:25,449 --> 01:27:27,742
Was it a Code Red? Yes.

1185
01:27:27,993 --> 01:27:29,994
Did Kendrick give the order? Yes.

1186
01:27:30,162 --> 01:27:32,079
Did you witness it? Did you witness it?

1187
01:27:32,247 --> 01:27:33,664
No. Then how do you know?

1188
01:27:33,832 --> 01:27:35,499
I know. Yeah, you know shit.

1189
01:27:35,667 --> 01:27:37,960
He was never gonna be transferred off that base.

1190
01:27:43,926 --> 01:27:47,178
Jessep was gonna keep him on the base, said he wanted him trained.

1191
01:27:47,346 --> 01:27:49,847
You signed the transfer order. Yeah, I know.

1192
01:27:50,015 --> 01:27:53,935
I signed them when you got to Cuba, five days after Santiago's death.

1193
01:27:57,648 --> 01:27:59,941
I'll get you immunity with the prosecutor.

1194
01:28:00,108 --> 01:28:04,570
In about four days you're gonna tell the court what you told me.

1195
01:28:04,738 --> 01:28:08,950
Right now I'll check you into a motel. We're gonna start from the beginning.

1196
01:28:09,117 --> 01:28:12,870
I don't want a deal, and I don't want immunity.

1197
01:28:13,038 --> 01:28:19,293
I'm not proud of what I have done, nor of what I am doing.

1198
01:28:20,587 --> 01:28:22,463
- Where is he? - The Downtown Lodge.

1199
01:28:22,631 --> 01:28:24,715
I want him guarded. That's a good idea.

1200
01:28:24,883 --> 01:28:27,385
My clearance code is 4115273. Clearance code?

1201
01:28:28,220 --> 01:28:29,637
I don't have a clearance code. You?

1202
01:28:29,805 --> 01:28:30,930
Danny. It's Jo Galloway.

1203
01:28:31,098 --> 01:28:32,139
I need to secure a witness.

1204
01:28:32,307 --> 01:28:35,476
He also said Jessep's lying about transportation off the base.

1205
01:28:35,644 --> 01:28:38,479
Jessep said that 6 the next morning was the first flight Santiago could have left on.

1206
01:28:38,647 --> 01:28:41,899
Markinson says there was one that left seven hours earlier.

1207
01:28:42,067 --> 01:28:44,026
That was impressive. Did you hear that?

1208
01:28:44,194 --> 01:28:47,738
Yeah. Sam, isn't there a record of flights?

1209
01:28:47,906 --> 01:28:50,574
You need the tower chief's log from Gitmo.

1210
01:28:50,742 --> 01:28:52,368
Get it. We're gonna win.

1211
01:28:52,536 --> 01:28:55,997
Jo, don't get crazy. We don't know Markinson, or the log book.

1212
01:28:56,164 --> 01:28:59,333
You concentrate on Downey, I'll talk to Ross.

1213
01:29:04,381 --> 01:29:09,635
Hey, Danny. Nice work today. The redirect on Barnes.

1214
01:29:09,803 --> 01:29:14,056
I have Markinson. Where is he?

1215
01:29:14,224 --> 01:29:18,436
Motel room in Northeast, six marshals outside the door. Take a sip.

1216
01:29:18,603 --> 01:29:20,896
The transfer Markinson signed is phony.

1217
01:29:21,064 --> 01:29:24,191
And Jessep lied about the first flight. We're getting the log.

1218
01:29:24,359 --> 01:29:25,401
Can I get you something?

1219
01:29:25,569 --> 01:29:26,777
Beer, please.

1220
01:29:26,945 --> 01:29:30,614
In the meantime, I'm gonna put Kendrick on the stand and have some fun.

1221
01:29:30,782 --> 01:29:33,284
All right. I have an obligation to tell you.

1222
01:29:33,452 --> 01:29:36,662
If you accuse Kendrick or Jessep of any crime without evidence,

1223
01:29:36,830 --> 01:29:39,457
you'll be court-martialed for misconduct

1224
01:29:39,624 --> 01:29:44,045
and that's gonna be stapled to every job application you ever fill out.

1225
01:29:45,839 --> 01:29:49,633
Markinson won't hold up, he's a crazy man.

1226
01:29:49,801 --> 01:29:52,970
I'm not saying this to intimidate you, I'm being your lawyer here.

1227
01:29:53,138 --> 01:29:56,974
Thanks. And I wanna tell you I think the whole fucking bunch of you are insane.

1228
01:29:57,142 --> 01:29:59,560
This code of honor makes me wanna beat the shit out of something!

1229
01:29:59,728 --> 01:30:03,481
Don't you dare lump me in with Jessep and Kendrick.

1230
01:30:03,648 --> 01:30:08,611
I'm your friend. Your clients don't belong in jail, but it's not my decision.

1231
01:30:08,779 --> 01:30:13,157
I represent the U.S. government without passion or prejudice,

1232
01:30:13,325 --> 01:30:16,243
- and my client has a case. - Here you go.

1233
01:30:20,290 --> 01:30:23,542
I want you to acknowledge that the judge advocate has made you aware

1234
01:30:23,710 --> 01:30:28,255
of the consequences of accusing a Marine officer without evidence.

1235
01:30:29,091 --> 01:30:30,966
I've been so advised.

1236
01:30:35,222 --> 01:30:42,103
You got bullied into that courtroom. By everyone. By Dawson. By Galloway.

1237
01:30:42,270 --> 01:30:44,522
Shit, I practically dared you.

1238
01:30:45,941 --> 01:30:49,276
You got bullied into that courtroom by the memory of a dead lawyer.

1239
01:30:55,450 --> 01:31:00,454
You're a lousy fucking softball player, Jack!

1240
01:31:01,957 --> 01:31:04,291
Your boys are going down, Danny.

1241
01:31:04,459 --> 01:31:07,503
I can't stop it anymore.

1242
01:31:11,466 --> 01:31:14,677
Was Santiago a good Marine?

1243
01:31:14,845 --> 01:31:16,846
I'd say he was average.

1244
01:31:17,013 --> 01:31:23,936
Your proficiency and conduct reports all indicate he was below average.

1245
01:31:27,524 --> 01:31:31,277
Yes, he was below average.

1246
01:31:31,444 --> 01:31:34,238
I did not see the need to trample on his grave.

1247
01:31:35,407 --> 01:31:40,161
We appreciate it, but you're under oath. I think we'd all like to hear the truth.

1248
01:31:40,328 --> 01:31:42,079
I'm aware of my oath.

1249
01:31:42,247 --> 01:31:47,293
These are the last three pro-con reports you signed for Lance Corporal Dawson.

1250
01:31:47,460 --> 01:31:53,549
He rated exceptional twice, but on June 9th he's below average.

1251
01:31:53,717 --> 01:31:57,595
I'd like to discuss that. That would be fine.

1252
01:31:57,762 --> 01:32:01,348
Dawson's ranking after the School of Infantry was perfect.

1253
01:32:01,516 --> 01:32:06,729
But unlike most of his class, he hasn't been promoted.

1254
01:32:06,897 --> 01:32:11,775
Was this report the reason? I'm sure it was.

1255
01:32:11,943 --> 01:32:16,238
Do you recall why he got this grade? I'm sure I don't.

1256
01:32:16,406 --> 01:32:20,117
I have many men in my charge. I write many reports.

1257
01:32:20,285 --> 01:32:25,956
Do you recall an incident involving a PFC Curtis Bell

1258
01:32:26,124 --> 01:32:28,751
stealing liquor from the officers' club?

1259
01:32:29,044 --> 01:32:30,753
Yes, I do.

1260
01:32:30,921 --> 01:32:33,255
Did you report Private Bell to the proper authorities?

1261
01:32:35,217 --> 01:32:37,259
I have two books at my bedside:

1262
01:32:37,427 --> 01:32:40,221
The Marine Corps Code of Conduct and the King James Bible.

1263
01:32:40,388 --> 01:32:45,851
The only proper authorities I'm aware of are Colonel Jessep and God.

1264
01:32:47,395 --> 01:32:52,733
Then you don't acknowledge this court as a proper authority?

1265
01:32:52,901 --> 01:32:57,780
Objection. Argumentative. Sustained. Watch yourself.

1266
01:32:57,948 --> 01:33:03,744
Did you report Private Bell? I thought very highly of him.

1267
01:33:03,912 --> 01:33:06,664
I didn't want his record tarnished by a charge.

1268
01:33:07,749 --> 01:33:10,668
You preferred it be handled within the unit?

1269
01:33:12,462 --> 01:33:14,338
Yes, I most certainly did.

1270
01:33:15,382 --> 01:33:18,801
Do you know what a Code Red is? Yes, I do.

1271
01:33:18,969 --> 01:33:22,096
Have you ever ordered one? No, I have not.

1272
01:33:22,264 --> 01:33:26,725
Did you order that Private Bell receive no food or drink

1273
01:33:26,893 --> 01:33:30,771
except water for a period of seven days?

1274
01:33:30,939 --> 01:33:35,526
You're distorting the truth. He was on barracks restriction.

1275
01:33:35,694 --> 01:33:42,658
He was given water and vitamins. His health was never in danger.

1276
01:33:42,867 --> 01:33:48,205
I'm sure it was lovely for him. But you did order the restriction.

1277
01:33:48,373 --> 01:33:52,459
You denied him food? Yes, I did.

1278
01:33:52,627 --> 01:33:59,049
Wouldn't this be called a Code Red? No.

1279
01:33:59,217 --> 01:34:04,555
Would the other 478 Marines at Guantánamo Bay consider it a Code Red?

1280
01:34:04,723 --> 01:34:09,184
The witness can't testify as to what 478 other men would say.

1281
01:34:09,352 --> 01:34:13,147
We object to this line of questioning as argumentative

1282
01:34:13,315 --> 01:34:15,566
and irrelevant badgering of the witness.

1283
01:34:15,734 --> 01:34:19,403
Sustained. And I would remind you

1284
01:34:19,571 --> 01:34:23,574
that you're questioning an officer with an impeccable service record.

1285
01:34:23,742 --> 01:34:25,326
Thank you, Your Honor.

1286
01:34:26,202 --> 01:34:32,916
Was Dawson rated below average for sneaking food to Private Bell?

1287
01:34:33,084 --> 01:34:36,420
Object! Not so fast. Lieutenant?

1288
01:34:38,089 --> 01:34:41,759
Dawson was given a below average rating

1289
01:34:42,552 --> 01:34:45,220
because he had committed a crime.

1290
01:34:45,388 --> 01:34:49,558
Crime? What crime did he commit?

1291
01:34:50,352 --> 01:34:56,523
Lieutenant Kendrick, Dawson brought a hungry guy some food.

1292
01:34:56,691 --> 01:35:01,779
What crime did he commit? He disobeyed an order.

1293
01:35:01,946 --> 01:35:07,493
And because he made a decision about the welfare of a Marine

1294
01:35:07,660 --> 01:35:11,121
that conflicted with your order, he was punished, right?

1295
01:35:11,289 --> 01:35:14,750
Lance Corporal Dawson disobeyed an order!

1296
01:35:14,918 --> 01:35:19,671
It wasn't a real order, was it? After all, it's peacetime.

1297
01:35:19,839 --> 01:35:22,966
He wasn't asked to advance on a beachhead.

1298
01:35:23,134 --> 01:35:27,471
Surely a Marine of Dawson's intelligence

1299
01:35:27,639 --> 01:35:30,474
can be trusted to determine which are the important orders

1300
01:35:30,642 --> 01:35:34,603
and which orders might, say, be morally questionable?

1301
01:35:35,980 --> 01:35:39,775
Lieutenant Kendrick? Can he?

1302
01:35:39,943 --> 01:35:43,404
Can Dawson determine on his own which orders to follow?

1303
01:35:43,571 --> 01:35:45,155
No, he cannot.

1304
01:35:45,323 --> 01:35:47,950
A lesson he learned after the Bell incident.

1305
01:35:48,118 --> 01:35:50,452
I would think so. You know so, don't you?

1306
01:35:50,662 --> 01:35:52,663
- Object! - Sustained.

1307
01:35:55,166 --> 01:35:57,876
Lieutenant Kendrick, one final question.

1308
01:35:58,878 --> 01:36:02,256
If you had ordered Dawson to give Santiago a Code Red,

1309
01:36:02,424 --> 01:36:04,716
I ordered them not to touch him!

1310
01:36:04,884 --> 01:36:06,510
Would he have disobeyed you again?

1311
01:36:06,678 --> 01:36:10,681
Lieutenant, don't answer that! You don't have to. I'm through.

1312
01:36:11,141 --> 01:36:18,856
Did you order Dawson and Downey to give Willy Santiago a Code Red?

1313
01:36:20,275 --> 01:36:22,734
Lieutenant Kendrick, did you…? No, I did not.

1314
01:36:22,902 --> 01:36:24,570
Thank you.

1315
01:36:28,533 --> 01:36:29,700
What's the word?

1316
01:36:29,868 --> 01:36:35,038
Well, I got the tower chief's log. Jessep's telling the truth.

1317
01:36:35,206 --> 01:36:38,375
Six a. M. Flight was the first plane. Let me see this.

1318
01:36:49,512 --> 01:36:53,056
Working late tonight, lieutenant? Oh, yeah.

1319
01:36:56,978 --> 01:37:00,606
There was no flight at 11:00! What the fuck are you trying to pull?!

1320
01:37:00,773 --> 01:37:07,779
The first flight left at 2300. It arrived at Andrews at 2 a. m.

1321
01:37:07,947 --> 01:37:11,074
Really? Then why isn't it listed in the tower chief's log?

1322
01:37:13,077 --> 01:37:18,916
Jessep. What? He fixed the logbook?

1323
01:37:19,083 --> 01:37:22,669
Maybe he can make it so it didn't take off, but I can prove it landed.

1324
01:37:22,837 --> 01:37:25,297
I'll get the logbook from Andrews.

1325
01:37:25,465 --> 01:37:30,260
You won't find anything. He can make a flight disappear?

1326
01:37:30,887 --> 01:37:34,932
Nathan Jessep is about to be appointed to the National Security Council.

1327
01:37:35,099 --> 01:37:38,894
You don't get there without knowing how to sidestep a few landmines.

1328
01:37:39,062 --> 01:37:41,813
He won't be able to sidestep you.

1329
01:37:41,981 --> 01:37:44,274
You still intend to put me on the stand?

1330
01:37:44,442 --> 01:37:47,277
Thursday morning. Ten o'clock.

1331
01:37:51,866 --> 01:37:55,619
There's gotta be someone who can testify to the flight. A ground crew member.

1332
01:37:55,787 --> 01:38:01,917
This isn't TWA. You know how many planes take off and land every day?

1333
01:38:02,085 --> 01:38:04,920
The ground crew isn't gonna remember it.

1334
01:38:05,088 --> 01:38:06,255
Well, how do you know…?

1335
01:38:06,506 --> 01:38:08,674
Forget the flight. Forget the flight.

1336
01:38:08,925 --> 01:38:13,679
Markinson will testify that the transfer was forged.

1337
01:38:13,846 --> 01:38:17,599
That and Downey's testimony really ought to be enough.

1338
01:38:23,356 --> 01:38:27,317
Why did you go into Santiago's room on the night of the 6th?

1339
01:38:27,485 --> 01:38:32,656
To give him a Code Red. And why did you do that?

1340
01:38:33,241 --> 01:38:37,828
I was ordered to by the platoon commander,

1341
01:38:37,996 --> 01:38:40,455
Lieutenant Jonathan James Kendrick.

1342
01:38:41,624 --> 01:38:43,667
You're gonna do fine.

1343
01:38:45,837 --> 01:38:48,171
Think we can rejoin the platoon soon?

1344
01:38:49,507 --> 01:38:51,508
Absolutely.

1345
01:38:54,804 --> 01:38:56,763
Remember the order of the questions? Are you sure?

1346
01:38:56,931 --> 01:38:58,181
Yes. And you'll use small words?

1347
01:38:58,349 --> 01:38:59,474
Yes. He gets rattled when…

1348
01:38:59,642 --> 01:39:01,351
Jo. Just go slow.

1349
01:39:01,519 --> 01:39:02,894
I'm gonna go slow. Okay.

1350
01:39:03,062 --> 01:39:04,521
And get him off as fast as you can.

1351
01:39:04,689 --> 01:39:05,981
JoAnne!

1352
01:39:06,149 --> 01:39:08,775
What? It's gonna be fine.

1353
01:39:11,571 --> 01:39:13,488
Dear Mr. and Mrs. Santiago,

1354
01:39:15,074 --> 01:39:17,367
L was William's executive officer.

1355
01:39:17,535 --> 01:39:19,911
L knew your son vaguely, which is to say I knew his name.

1356
01:39:21,873 --> 01:39:26,793
Soon, the trial of the two men charged with his death will be concluded,

1357
01:39:26,961 --> 01:39:33,342
and the jury will try to offer you an explanation as to why he's dead.

1358
01:39:33,509 --> 01:39:37,346
For my part, I've done as much as I can to bring the truth to light.

1359
01:39:37,513 --> 01:39:39,222
And the truth is this:

1360
01:39:39,390 --> 01:39:41,892
Your son is dead for only one reason:

1361
01:39:42,268 --> 01:39:44,895
I wasn't strong enough to stop it.

1362
01:39:45,063 --> 01:39:49,024
Always, Lieutenant Colonel Matthew Andrew Markinson,

1363
01:39:49,192 --> 01:39:50,901
United States Marine Corps.

1364
01:39:56,199 --> 01:39:59,826
Private, I want you to tell us one last time:

1365
01:39:59,994 --> 01:40:05,916
Why did you go to Santiago's room on the night of September 6th?

1366
01:40:06,084 --> 01:40:10,379
A Code Red was ordered by Platoon Commander Kendrick.

1367
01:40:10,546 --> 01:40:14,424
Thank you. Your witness.

1368
01:40:18,930 --> 01:40:22,015
The week of 2 September, the switch log

1369
01:40:22,183 --> 01:40:25,936
has you down at Post 39 until 1600. Right?

1370
01:40:26,104 --> 01:40:32,609
They keep that log pretty good. How far is Post 39 from barracks?

1371
01:40:32,777 --> 01:40:38,990
It's a ways, sir. It's a hike. About how far by jeep?

1372
01:40:40,284 --> 01:40:42,536
About 10, 15 minutes, sir.

1373
01:40:42,704 --> 01:40:46,623
You ever had to walk it? Yes, sir, that day. Friday.

1374
01:40:46,791 --> 01:40:51,712
The pickup private… That's what we call the guy that drops us off.

1375
01:40:51,879 --> 01:40:54,506
Also because he can get girls in New York City.

1376
01:40:56,008 --> 01:40:57,968
…He got a flat right at 39.

1377
01:40:58,136 --> 01:41:03,056
He pulled up and bam, blow-out with no spare. So we had to jog back to barracks.

1378
01:41:03,224 --> 01:41:09,938
And if it's 10 or 15 minutes by jeep, it must be an hour by foot, right?

1379
01:41:10,106 --> 01:41:13,900
We did it in 45 flat, sir. Not bad.

1380
01:41:16,195 --> 01:41:22,617
You've said your assault on Santiago was ordered by Lieutenant Kendrick

1381
01:41:22,785 --> 01:41:27,622
in your barracks room at 1620, am I right?

1382
01:41:27,790 --> 01:41:29,082
Yes, sir.

1383
01:41:29,250 --> 01:41:34,171
You said you weren't back until 1645.

1384
01:41:34,338 --> 01:41:35,589
Sir?

1385
01:41:35,757 --> 01:41:42,012
If you weren't back until 1645, how could you be in your room at 1620?

1386
01:41:42,764 --> 01:41:45,849
Well, you see, sir, there was a blow-out…

1387
01:41:46,017 --> 01:41:49,853
Did you ever actually hear Lieutenant Kendrick order a Code Red?

1388
01:41:50,021 --> 01:41:52,189
Well, Hal said that…

1389
01:41:52,356 --> 01:41:57,027
Did you ever actually hear Lieutenant Kendrick order a Code Red?

1390
01:41:58,070 --> 01:42:02,157
No, sir. I'd like to request a recess.

1391
01:42:02,325 --> 01:42:03,617
Why did you go into Santiago's room?

1392
01:42:03,785 --> 01:42:06,369
The witness has rights! He has been read his rights.

1393
01:42:06,537 --> 01:42:07,954
The question will be repeated.

1394
01:42:08,122 --> 01:42:09,414
Why did you go to Santiago's room?

1395
01:42:09,582 --> 01:42:12,584
- Hal? - Did Dawson tell you to?

1396
01:42:12,752 --> 01:42:14,461
Hal? Don't look at him!

1397
01:42:14,629 --> 01:42:17,214
Hal? Answer the captain's question.

1398
01:42:20,551 --> 01:42:25,722
Yes. I was given an order by Lance Corporal Dawson

1399
01:42:25,890 --> 01:42:27,641
and I followed it.

1400
01:42:49,247 --> 01:42:52,123
Where do you think he is?

1401
01:42:52,917 --> 01:42:56,127
As far as Downey was concerned, it was an order from Kendrick.

1402
01:42:56,295 --> 01:42:59,631
It doesn't matter that he didn't hear firsthand.

1403
01:43:05,137 --> 01:43:07,389
Danny, I'm sorry.

1404
01:43:08,099 --> 01:43:09,891
Don't worry about it.

1405
01:43:10,059 --> 01:43:15,188
All we need to do is call some witnesses to talk about implied orders,

1406
01:43:15,356 --> 01:43:18,108
or call Downey back before we get to Dawson.

1407
01:43:18,776 --> 01:43:23,613
Maybe we could get Dawson charged with the Kennedy assassination?

1408
01:43:26,784 --> 01:43:33,290
Are you drunk? Pretty much. Yeah.

1409
01:43:34,166 --> 01:43:37,627
I'll put on a pot of coffee. We've got a long night's work ahead.

1410
01:43:38,796 --> 01:43:44,259
She's gonna make coffee? That's nice.

1411
01:43:48,180 --> 01:43:54,394
Downey wasn't in his room. He wasn't even there.

1412
01:43:54,562 --> 01:43:59,357
That was important information, don't you think?

1413
01:44:00,109 --> 01:44:04,696
Danny, it was a setback. And I'm sorry.

1414
01:44:04,864 --> 01:44:08,950
But we fix it and move on to Markinson.

1415
01:44:09,118 --> 01:44:10,619
Markinson's dead.

1416
01:44:16,542 --> 01:44:20,879
You really got to hand it to those federal marshals, boy.

1417
01:44:21,047 --> 01:44:27,177
He didn't hang himself by his shoelaces, or slash his wrists with a butter knife.

1418
01:44:29,388 --> 01:44:36,144
This guy got into full dress uniform, drew a nickel-plated pistol,

1419
01:44:36,312 --> 01:44:38,813
and fired a bullet into his mouth.

1420
01:44:42,693 --> 01:44:47,322
Anyway, since we're out of witnesses, I thought I'd drink a little.

1421
01:44:47,490 --> 01:44:52,535
I still think we can win. Maybe you should drink a little.

1422
01:44:52,787 --> 01:44:57,624
In the morning, we'll ask Randolph for a continuance, 24 hours.

1423
01:44:57,792 --> 01:45:00,961
Why would we do that? To subpoena Colonel Jessep.

1424
01:45:02,046 --> 01:45:03,755
What? Listen for a second.

1425
01:45:03,923 --> 01:45:06,675
Just hear me out. No! I won't listen.

1426
01:45:06,842 --> 01:45:09,427
Your passion is compelling, but useless.

1427
01:45:09,595 --> 01:45:13,515
Louden Downey needed a trial lawyer today.

1428
01:45:15,810 --> 01:45:20,105
You chickenshit. You just want an excuse to give up.

1429
01:45:21,273 --> 01:45:23,149
It's over.

1430
01:45:23,317 --> 01:45:25,652
Why did you ask Jessep for the transfer order?

1431
01:45:25,820 --> 01:45:28,446
In Cuba, why did you ask him? What does it matter?

1432
01:45:28,614 --> 01:45:31,199
I wanted the damn transfer order! Bullshit!

1433
01:45:31,367 --> 01:45:34,744
You could have gotten it by calling any one of a dozen departments.

1434
01:45:34,912 --> 01:45:39,582
You didn't want the order. You wanted to see Jessep's reaction.

1435
01:45:39,750 --> 01:45:42,711
You had an instinct and it was confirmed by Markinson.

1436
01:45:42,878 --> 01:45:45,714
Now let's put Jessep on the stand and end this thing.

1437
01:45:45,881 --> 01:45:52,178
What possible good would that do? He ordered the Code Red.

1438
01:45:52,346 --> 01:45:58,643
He did? That's great! And of course, you have proof?

1439
01:45:58,811 --> 01:46:02,939
Oh, I'm sorry, I forgot. You were sick that day at law school.

1440
01:46:03,107 --> 01:46:05,442
You put him on the stand and get it from him.

1441
01:46:05,609 --> 01:46:09,821
We get it from him! Yes, no problem. We get it from him.

1442
01:46:09,989 --> 01:46:14,200
Colonel Jessep, isn't it true you ordered the Code Red on Santiago?

1443
01:46:15,536 --> 01:46:18,455
I'm sorry, time's run out! What do we have for the losers, judge?

1444
01:46:18,622 --> 01:46:22,834
Well, for our defendants, it's a lifetime at exotic Fort Leavenworth!

1445
01:46:23,002 --> 01:46:28,757
And for Defense Counsel Kaffee, that's right, it's a court-martial!

1446
01:46:28,924 --> 01:46:34,345
After falsely accusing a decorated officer of conspiracy and perjury,

1447
01:46:34,513 --> 01:46:38,016
Lieutenant Kaffee will have a long and prosperous career

1448
01:46:38,184 --> 01:46:43,271
teaching typewriter maintenance at a women's school!

1449
01:46:43,439 --> 01:46:49,652
Thank you for playing Follow the Advice of the Galactically Stupid!

1450
01:47:11,467 --> 01:47:14,636
I'm sorry I lost you your set of steak knives.

1451
01:47:31,612 --> 01:47:35,281
Stop cleaning up.

1452
01:47:37,201 --> 01:47:41,412
Sam, stop cleaning up.

1453
01:47:49,004 --> 01:47:54,008
You want a drink? Yeah.

1454
01:48:10,067 --> 01:48:13,111
Is your father proud of you? Don't do this to yourself.

1455
01:48:13,279 --> 01:48:15,029
I'll bet he is.

1456
01:48:15,906 --> 01:48:19,117
I'll bet he bores the shit out of the neighbors and relatives.

1457
01:48:19,285 --> 01:48:21,703
Sam's made law review.

1458
01:48:21,871 --> 01:48:27,959
He's got a big case he's making. He's making an argument.

1459
01:48:32,381 --> 01:48:38,261
I think my father would have enjoyed seeing me graduate from law school.

1460
01:48:40,222 --> 01:48:44,309
I think he would have liked that a lot.

1461
01:48:45,394 --> 01:48:48,396
I ever tell you I wrote a paper about your father in college?

1462
01:48:49,398 --> 01:48:50,899
Yeah?

1463
01:48:51,567 --> 01:48:56,946
One of the best trial lawyers ever. Yes, he was.

1464
01:48:57,198 --> 01:49:02,243
But if I were Dawson and Downey, and had to choose you or him,

1465
01:49:02,411 --> 01:49:05,455
I'd choose you any day of the week, and twice on Sunday.

1466
01:49:06,123 --> 01:49:09,626
You should have seen yourself thunder away at Kendrick.

1467
01:49:12,087 --> 01:49:16,799
Would you put Jessep on the stand? No.

1468
01:49:17,426 --> 01:49:22,347
Do you think my father would have? With the evidence we got?

1469
01:49:22,514 --> 01:49:25,308
Not in a million years.

1470
01:49:25,476 --> 01:49:29,020
But here's the thing, and we can't get around this:

1471
01:49:29,188 --> 01:49:31,105
Neither Lionel Kaffee nor Sam Weinberg

1472
01:49:31,273 --> 01:49:36,361
are lead counsel for the defense in U.S. v. Dawson and Downey.

1473
01:49:36,528 --> 01:49:40,990
So there's really only one question: What would you do?

1474
01:49:49,375 --> 01:49:53,753
Jo. JoAnne! Jo, get in the car.

1475
01:49:53,921 --> 01:49:57,298
JoAnne, please get in the car! Look…

1476
01:49:58,759 --> 01:50:02,929
JoAnne! I apologize. I was angry.

1477
01:50:03,097 --> 01:50:05,682
I'm sorry about what I said.

1478
01:50:05,849 --> 01:50:09,936
I'm gonna put Jessep on the stand!

1479
01:50:28,372 --> 01:50:30,206
What do you suggest we do?

1480
01:50:30,374 --> 01:50:32,917
Hit Jessep with the phony transfer order.

1481
01:50:33,085 --> 01:50:35,378
Without a witness? We have a witness.

1482
01:50:35,546 --> 01:50:36,546
A dead witness.

1483
01:50:36,714 --> 01:50:39,340
To a lesser attorney, that'd be a problem.

1484
01:50:39,508 --> 01:50:44,387
Look. Last night he's swimming in Jack Daniel's, now he can leap tall buildings in a single bound.

1485
01:50:44,555 --> 01:50:49,600
I'm getting my second wind. Sit down, both of you. Good.

1486
01:50:49,768 --> 01:50:51,728
Jessep told Kendrick to order the Code Red,

1487
01:50:51,895 --> 01:50:53,938
Kendrick did, our clients followed orders.

1488
01:50:54,106 --> 01:50:59,360
The cover-up isn't our case. To win, Jessep has to say he gave the order.

1489
01:50:59,945 --> 01:51:03,156
And you can get him to say it? I think he wants to say it!

1490
01:51:03,324 --> 01:51:06,451
I think he's pissed off he's gotta hide. I think he wants to say

1491
01:51:06,618 --> 01:51:09,746
he made a decision, and that's the end of it!

1492
01:51:09,913 --> 01:51:12,040
He eats breakfast 300 yards away

1493
01:51:12,207 --> 01:51:15,501
from 4000 Cubans that are trained to kill him.

1494
01:51:15,669 --> 01:51:17,754
And no one tells him how to run his unit,

1495
01:51:17,921 --> 01:51:20,840
least of all the Harvard mouth in his faggoty white uniform.

1496
01:51:21,008 --> 01:51:25,428
I need to shake him. I'll lead him right where he's dying to go.

1497
01:51:25,596 --> 01:51:28,264
That's it? That's the plan? That's the plan.

1498
01:51:28,432 --> 01:51:30,099
How are you going to do it?

1499
01:51:30,267 --> 01:51:33,770
- I have no idea. I need my bat. - Your what?

1500
01:51:33,937 --> 01:51:36,272
I need my bat. I think better with it. Where is it?

1501
01:51:36,440 --> 01:51:39,609
I put it in the closet. You put it in the closet?

1502
01:51:39,860 --> 01:51:41,527
I was tripping on it.

1503
01:51:41,695 --> 01:51:43,780
Don't ever put that bat in the closet.

1504
01:51:59,171 --> 01:52:01,839
Stay here. I'm going to the office for a while.

1505
01:52:04,635 --> 01:52:07,220
He does think better with that bat.

1506
01:52:28,659 --> 01:52:32,995
Hello? Sam, I need you to do something.

1507
01:52:36,458 --> 01:52:39,752
What's going on? Gotta go out to Andrews.

1508
01:53:03,360 --> 01:53:04,861
Where's Sam? He's on his way.

1509
01:53:05,028 --> 01:53:07,029
Did he get the guys? Yeah.

1510
01:53:07,197 --> 01:53:12,243
Listen, can I talk to you for a second? Yeah, sure.

1511
01:53:23,297 --> 01:53:24,714
How are you feeling?

1512
01:53:26,133 --> 01:53:30,511
Well, I think Jessep's gonna have his hands full today.

1513
01:53:32,931 --> 01:53:37,310
Listen, Danny, when you're out there today,

1514
01:53:37,478 --> 01:53:44,358
if you feel like it's not gonna happen, like he's not going to say it,

1515
01:53:44,526 --> 01:53:49,572
don't go for it. You could get into trouble.

1516
01:53:50,324 --> 01:53:54,660
I'm special counsel for Internal Affairs. I'm telling you you could get in trouble.

1517
01:53:54,828 --> 01:54:00,958
You're not suggesting that I back off a material witness?

1518
01:54:01,418 --> 01:54:04,253
If you think you can't get him, yeah.

1519
01:54:06,632 --> 01:54:08,216
All rise!

1520
01:54:13,305 --> 01:54:15,723
Where's Sam? He's on his way.

1521
01:54:21,647 --> 01:54:22,897
Call your first witness.

1522
01:54:23,065 --> 01:54:25,525
Where is he? He'll be here. Don't worry.

1523
01:54:25,692 --> 01:54:28,444
Lieutenant! Call your witness.

1524
01:54:35,327 --> 01:54:37,745
Defense calls Colonel Nathan Jessep.

1525
01:54:54,346 --> 01:54:57,306
Colonel Jessep, raise your right hand, please, sir.

1526
01:54:57,474 --> 01:55:01,686
Do you solemnly swear to tell the truth,

1527
01:55:01,853 --> 01:55:04,355
the whole truth, and nothing but the truth?

1528
01:55:04,648 --> 01:55:09,068
Yes, I do. Have a seat, please, sir.

1529
01:55:09,236 --> 01:55:12,488
State your name, rank and current billet for the record.

1530
01:55:13,323 --> 01:55:16,867
Colonel Jessep, Commanding Officer, Marine Ground Forces,

1531
01:55:17,035 --> 01:55:19,078
Guantánamo Bay, Cuba.

1532
01:55:19,246 --> 01:55:22,665
Thank you, sir. He's not here.

1533
01:55:27,504 --> 01:55:31,048
When you learned of Santiago's letter to the NIS,

1534
01:55:31,216 --> 01:55:34,844
you had a meeting with your two senior officers, is that right?

1535
01:55:35,012 --> 01:55:36,846
Yes.

1536
01:55:37,014 --> 01:55:39,682
Platoon Commander Kendrick

1537
01:55:39,850 --> 01:55:43,561
and the executive officer, Lieutenant Colonel Markinson.

1538
01:55:44,104 --> 01:55:45,187
Yes.

1539
01:55:45,355 --> 01:55:49,775
And, at present, Markinson is dead, is that right?

1540
01:55:49,943 --> 01:55:53,821
What is the counselor implying?

1541
01:55:53,989 --> 01:55:57,366
Simply that at present Markinson is not alive.

1542
01:55:57,534 --> 01:56:01,203
Surely Colonel Jessep doesn't need to confirm that.

1543
01:56:01,371 --> 01:56:05,625
I wasn't sure he was aware that Markinson took his own life two days ago.

1544
01:56:07,044 --> 01:56:11,130
The witness, the court and now the court members are aware.

1545
01:56:11,590 --> 01:56:16,552
We thank you for bringing it up. Move on, lieutenant.

1546
01:56:16,720 --> 01:56:18,387
Yes, sir.

1547
01:56:18,555 --> 01:56:22,099
At this meeting, you gave Kendrick an order, right?

1548
01:56:22,267 --> 01:56:26,479
I told him to tell his men not to touch Santiago.

1549
01:56:26,813 --> 01:56:29,523
And did you give an order to Markinson as well?

1550
01:56:29,691 --> 01:56:34,987
I ordered him to have Santiago transferred off the base immediately.

1551
01:56:35,155 --> 01:56:40,826
Why? I felt his life might be in danger.

1552
01:56:41,244 --> 01:56:45,581
Grave danger? Is there another kind?

1553
01:56:48,502 --> 01:56:52,588
This is the transfer order that you and Markinson co-signed,

1554
01:56:52,756 --> 01:56:56,884
ordering that Santiago fly out at 6 the next morning.

1555
01:56:57,052 --> 01:57:02,014
Was that the first flight off the base? The 0600 was the first flight.

1556
01:57:06,228 --> 01:57:09,271
You flew here today, is that right? Yes.

1557
01:57:09,439 --> 01:57:14,276
You're wearing your dress uniform. As are you, lieutenant.

1558
01:57:14,444 --> 01:57:18,989
Did you wear it on the plane? Is this dialogue relevant to anything?

1559
01:57:19,157 --> 01:57:23,285
We didn't have a chance to depose this witness. I'd ask the court for a little latitude.

1560
01:57:23,453 --> 01:57:27,581
A very little latitude. Colonel?

1561
01:57:27,749 --> 01:57:29,667
I wore utilities on the plane.

1562
01:57:29,835 --> 01:57:32,795
You brought your dress uniform? Yes.

1563
01:57:32,963 --> 01:57:35,965
Toothbrush, shaving kit, underwear? Your Honor!

1564
01:57:36,133 --> 01:57:38,551
Is his underwear a matter of national security?

1565
01:57:38,719 --> 01:57:42,138
Gentlemen. You'd better get somewhere fast with this, lieutenant.

1566
01:57:42,305 --> 01:57:44,306
Yes, sir. Colonel?

1567
01:57:45,183 --> 01:57:49,145
I brought a change of clothes and some personal items.

1568
01:57:49,771 --> 01:57:51,230
Thank you.

1569
01:57:51,398 --> 01:57:54,817
After Dawson and Downey's arrest on the night of the 6th,

1570
01:57:54,985 --> 01:57:59,280
Santiago's barracks room was sealed off, and its contents inventoried.

1571
01:57:59,448 --> 01:58:04,034
Four pairs of camouflage pants, three khaki shirts, three pairs of boots.

1572
01:58:04,202 --> 01:58:09,498
Four pairs green socks… Is there a question in our future?

1573
01:58:09,833 --> 01:58:12,501
Lieutenant, state your question.

1574
01:58:13,003 --> 01:58:15,588
I'm wondering why Santiago wasn't packed.

1575
01:58:18,383 --> 01:58:21,469
Tell you what, we'll get back to that one in a minute.

1576
01:58:21,636 --> 01:58:25,473
This is a record of all phone calls from your base in the past 24 hours.

1577
01:58:25,640 --> 01:58:28,893
After being subpoenaed, you made three calls.

1578
01:58:29,060 --> 01:58:31,520
Do you recognize those numbers?

1579
01:58:31,688 --> 01:58:37,443
I called Colonel Fitzhughes to let him know I'd be in town.

1580
01:58:37,611 --> 01:58:43,282
The second was to arrange a meeting with Congressman Richman.

1581
01:58:43,450 --> 01:58:48,537
And the third call was to my sister. Why did you make that call?

1582
01:58:48,997 --> 01:58:51,165
I thought she might like to have dinner.

1583
01:58:51,333 --> 01:58:53,125
Your Honor. I'll put a stop to this.

1584
01:58:53,293 --> 01:58:57,463
These are the phone records from Gitmo for September 6th.

1585
01:58:57,631 --> 01:59:02,927
And these are 14 letters that Santiago wrote in nine months

1586
01:59:03,094 --> 01:59:06,347
requesting, begging for a transfer.

1587
01:59:06,515 --> 01:59:09,308
Upon hearing the news he was getting it,

1588
01:59:09,476 --> 01:59:11,268
Santiago was so excited,

1589
01:59:11,436 --> 01:59:15,689
you know how many people he called? Zero! Nobody.

1590
01:59:16,107 --> 01:59:19,568
Not one call to his parents, saying he was coming home.

1591
01:59:19,736 --> 01:59:23,197
Not one call to a friend, saying, Can you pick me up?

1592
01:59:23,365 --> 01:59:29,411
He was asleep at midnight, and you say he had a flight in six hours.

1593
01:59:29,579 --> 01:59:35,918
Yet everything he owned was in his closet or his footlocker.

1594
01:59:36,086 --> 01:59:39,588
You were leaving for one day, you packed and made three calls.

1595
01:59:39,756 --> 01:59:45,970
Santiago was leaving for the rest of his life

1596
01:59:46,137 --> 01:59:50,975
and he hadn't called a soul, and he hadn't packed a thing.

1597
01:59:54,688 --> 01:59:56,272
Can you explain that?

1598
01:59:59,150 --> 02:00:03,863
Fact is, there was no transfer order. Santiago wasn't going anywhere, right?

1599
02:00:04,030 --> 02:00:09,785
Objection! Lieutenant Kaffee is trying to smear a high-ranking Marine officer,

1600
02:00:09,953 --> 02:00:12,288
desperately hoping to suggest impropriety

1601
02:00:12,455 --> 02:00:17,585
and win points with the court. I recommend that he be reprimanded

1602
02:00:17,752 --> 02:00:21,589
and the witness be excused with apologies.

1603
02:00:22,173 --> 02:00:28,596
Overruled. The objection is noted. Colonel?

1604
02:00:32,684 --> 02:00:37,146
Is this funny, sir? No, it's not. It's tragic.

1605
02:00:37,314 --> 02:00:39,940
Do you have an answer? Absolutely.

1606
02:00:40,108 --> 02:00:44,153
My answer is I don't have the first damn clue.

1607
02:00:44,321 --> 02:00:50,659
Maybe he was an early riser. Maybe he didn't have any friends.

1608
02:00:50,827 --> 02:00:54,246
I'm an educated man, but I can't speak intelligently

1609
02:00:54,414 --> 02:00:58,000
about the travel habits of William Santiago.

1610
02:00:58,168 --> 02:01:02,963
What I do know is that he was set to leave the base at 0600.

1611
02:01:03,798 --> 02:01:08,719
Now, are these really the questions that I was called here to answer?

1612
02:01:08,887 --> 02:01:11,347
Phone calls and foot lockers?

1613
02:01:11,806 --> 02:01:15,142
Please tell me you have something more, lieutenant.

1614
02:01:15,352 --> 02:01:18,938
These two Marines are on trial for their lives.

1615
02:01:19,105 --> 02:01:23,442
Please tell me their lawyer hasn't pinned their hopes to a phone bill.

1616
02:01:26,279 --> 02:01:29,365
Do you have any other questions for me, counselor?

1617
02:01:38,249 --> 02:01:40,876
Lieutenant Kaffee?

1618
02:01:48,218 --> 02:01:52,554
Lieutenant, do you have anything further for this witness?

1619
02:01:59,354 --> 02:02:04,149
Thanks, Danny. I love Washington. Excuse me. I didn't dismiss you.

1620
02:02:05,151 --> 02:02:09,780
I beg your pardon? I'm not through with my examination.

1621
02:02:09,948 --> 02:02:11,573
Sit down.

1622
02:02:13,410 --> 02:02:15,911
Colonel. What's that?

1623
02:02:16,079 --> 02:02:20,416
I'd appreciate if he would address me as colonel or sir. I've earned it.

1624
02:02:21,001 --> 02:02:24,545
Defense counsel will address the witness as colonel or sir.

1625
02:02:24,713 --> 02:02:27,756
I don't know what the hell kind of unit you're running here.

1626
02:02:27,924 --> 02:02:31,510
And the witness will address this court as judge or Your Honor.

1627
02:02:31,678 --> 02:02:33,512
I'm quite certain I've earned it.

1628
02:02:34,264 --> 02:02:38,225
Take your seat, colonel.

1629
02:02:41,396 --> 02:02:45,566
What shall we discuss now? My favorite color?

1630
02:02:46,568 --> 02:02:49,194
Colonel, the 6 a. M. Flight was the first off the base?

1631
02:02:49,362 --> 02:02:50,946
Yes.

1632
02:02:51,114 --> 02:02:55,200
There wasn't one seven hours earlier and landed at Andrews at 2 a. m.?

1633
02:02:55,368 --> 02:02:58,245
I think we've covered this, haven't we?

1634
02:02:59,080 --> 02:03:04,293
These are the tower chief's logs for Guantánamo Bay and Andrews.

1635
02:03:04,794 --> 02:03:10,299
There's no flight at 11 p. M., and no arrival at 2 a. m.

1636
02:03:10,467 --> 02:03:13,802
I'd like to admit them as Defense Exhibits Alpha and Bravo.

1637
02:03:13,970 --> 02:03:17,389
You're admitting evidence of a flight that never existed.

1638
02:03:17,557 --> 02:03:19,975
We believe it did, sir.

1639
02:03:20,143 --> 02:03:26,148
We call Airmen O'Malley and Rodriguez of Andrews Air Base.

1640
02:03:26,316 --> 02:03:28,025
They weren't on the list.

1641
02:03:28,193 --> 02:03:33,739
Rebuttal witnesses, Your Honor, called to refute testimony.

1642
02:03:33,907 --> 02:03:36,742
I'll allow the witnesses. This is ridiculous!

1643
02:03:37,077 --> 02:03:38,410
Colonel, a moment ago…

1644
02:03:38,578 --> 02:03:44,333
Check the logs, for chrissake! We'll get to that in a minute.

1645
02:03:45,418 --> 02:03:51,465
You said you ordered Kendrick to say that Santiago wasn't to be touched.

1646
02:03:51,633 --> 02:03:53,092
That's right.

1647
02:03:53,259 --> 02:03:57,763
He was clear on what you wanted? Crystal.

1648
02:03:58,681 --> 02:04:03,018
Could he have ignored the order? Ignored the order?

1649
02:04:03,186 --> 02:04:06,188
Or forgot about it? No.

1650
02:04:06,356 --> 02:04:10,359
Any chance he could have thought, The old man is wrong?

1651
02:04:10,985 --> 02:04:12,361
No.

1652
02:04:12,529 --> 02:04:18,033
When Lieutenant Kendrick spoke to the platoon, any chance they ignored him?

1653
02:04:19,494 --> 02:04:23,413
You ever served in the infantry, son? No, sir.

1654
02:04:23,581 --> 02:04:27,126
Ever served in a forward area? No, sir.

1655
02:04:27,544 --> 02:04:32,881
Ever put your life in another man's hands, and his in yours?

1656
02:04:33,049 --> 02:04:34,383
No, sir.

1657
02:04:34,551 --> 02:04:39,096
We follow orders, son. We follow orders or people die.

1658
02:04:39,264 --> 02:04:42,391
It's that simple. Are we clear?

1659
02:04:43,101 --> 02:04:44,351
Yes, sir.

1660
02:04:44,519 --> 02:04:48,897
Are we clear? Crystal.

1661
02:04:50,608 --> 02:04:54,820
Just one more question, before I call Airmen O'Malley and Rodriguez.

1662
02:04:56,114 --> 02:05:00,409
If you ordered that Santiago wasn't to be touched

1663
02:05:00,910 --> 02:05:04,705
and your orders are always followed,

1664
02:05:04,873 --> 02:05:09,084
then why would Santiago be in danger?

1665
02:05:10,044 --> 02:05:13,755
Why would it be necessary to transfer him off the base?

1666
02:05:19,554 --> 02:05:23,849
Santiago was a substandard Marine. He was being transferred…

1667
02:05:24,017 --> 02:05:27,978
You said he was being transferred because he was in grave danger.

1668
02:05:28,146 --> 02:05:30,272
That's correct. You said he was in danger.

1669
02:05:30,440 --> 02:05:32,608
I said, grave danger? You said… I recall…

1670
02:05:32,775 --> 02:05:34,276
I can have the reporter read…

1671
02:05:34,444 --> 02:05:37,362
I know what I said! I don't have to have it read back…

1672
02:05:37,530 --> 02:05:41,033
Then why the two orders? Colonel?

1673
02:05:43,161 --> 02:05:45,621
Sometimes men take matters into their own hands.

1674
02:05:45,788 --> 02:05:48,707
No, sir. You made it clear your men never do.

1675
02:05:48,875 --> 02:05:53,587
Your men follow orders or people die. So Santiago wasn't in danger, right?

1676
02:05:53,755 --> 02:05:55,881
You snotty little bastard.

1677
02:05:56,049 --> 02:05:57,466
Your Honor, I ask for a recess.

1678
02:05:57,634 --> 02:05:59,259
I'd like an answer.

1679
02:05:59,427 --> 02:06:01,220
The court will wait for an answer.

1680
02:06:02,055 --> 02:06:07,351
If Lieutenant Kendrick gave an order that Santiago wasn't to be touched,

1681
02:06:07,518 --> 02:06:12,272
then why did he have to be transferred? Colonel?

1682
02:06:12,440 --> 02:06:16,193
Kendrick ordered a Code Red because that's what you told him to do!

1683
02:06:16,361 --> 02:06:17,486
Object!

1684
02:06:17,654 --> 02:06:23,867
And when it went bad, you signed a phony transfer and doctored the logs!

1685
02:06:24,035 --> 02:06:25,702
You coerced the doctor!

1686
02:06:25,870 --> 02:06:28,997
Colonel Jessep, did you order the Code Red?

1687
02:06:29,165 --> 02:06:32,417
You don't have to answer that. I'll answer the question.

1688
02:06:32,585 --> 02:06:34,836
You want answers? I think I'm entitled!

1689
02:06:35,004 --> 02:06:37,256
You want answers? I want the truth!

1690
02:06:37,423 --> 02:06:40,550
You can't handle the truth!

1691
02:06:40,718 --> 02:06:45,013
Son, we live in a world that has walls, and those walls have to be guarded by men with guns.

1692
02:06:45,181 --> 02:06:49,685
Who's gonna do it? You? You, Lieutenant Weinberg?

1693
02:06:49,852 --> 02:06:53,689
I have a greater responsibility than you can possibly fathom.

1694
02:06:53,856 --> 02:06:57,192
You weep for Santiago and you curse the Marines.

1695
02:06:57,360 --> 02:07:01,196
You have that luxury. The luxury of not knowing what I know:

1696
02:07:01,364 --> 02:07:05,325
That Santiago's death, while tragic, probably saved lives.

1697
02:07:05,493 --> 02:07:11,290
And my existence, while grotesque and incomprehensible to you, saves lives!

1698
02:07:11,457 --> 02:07:13,417
You don't want the truth because deep down,

1699
02:07:13,584 --> 02:07:15,711
in places you don't talk about at parties,

1700
02:07:15,878 --> 02:07:20,590
you want me on that wall. You need me on that wall.

1701
02:07:20,758 --> 02:07:25,262
We use words like honor, code, loyalty.

1702
02:07:25,430 --> 02:07:28,849
We use them as the backbone of a life spent defending something.

1703
02:07:29,017 --> 02:07:31,059
You use them as a punch line!

1704
02:07:31,227 --> 02:07:34,980
I have neither the time nor inclination to explain myself

1705
02:07:35,148 --> 02:07:39,609
to a man who rises and sleeps under the blanket of the freedom I provide,

1706
02:07:39,777 --> 02:07:42,154
and then questions the manner in which I provide it!

1707
02:07:42,322 --> 02:07:45,365
I would rather you just said thank you and went on your way.

1708
02:07:45,533 --> 02:07:49,286
Otherwise, I suggest you pick up a weapon and stand a post.

1709
02:07:49,454 --> 02:07:54,249
Either way, I don't give a damn what you think you are entitled to!

1710
02:07:54,417 --> 02:07:56,918
Did you order the Code Red? I did the job…

1711
02:07:57,086 --> 02:08:00,422
Did you order the Code Red? You're goddamn right I did!

1712
02:08:11,476 --> 02:08:14,311
I suggest the members be dismissed

1713
02:08:14,479 --> 02:08:17,898
so we can move to an article 39A session.

1714
02:08:18,066 --> 02:08:22,694
The witness has rights. Captain Ross?

1715
02:08:27,241 --> 02:08:28,867
Jack?

1716
02:08:33,873 --> 02:08:37,250
The members of the court will retire until further instructed.

1717
02:08:37,960 --> 02:08:39,920
All rise.

1718
02:08:40,463 --> 02:08:42,756
What the hell is this?

1719
02:08:42,924 --> 02:08:46,510
Colonel, what's going on? I did my job, I'd do it again.

1720
02:08:46,677 --> 02:08:51,473
I'm going back to my base. You're not going anywhere.

1721
02:08:51,641 --> 02:08:55,936
- MP's, guard the colonel! - Yes, sir.

1722
02:08:57,188 --> 02:08:59,856
Captain Ross. What the hell is this?

1723
02:09:00,108 --> 02:09:02,484
Colonel Jessep, you have the right to remain silent.

1724
02:09:02,652 --> 02:09:07,072
I'm being charged with a crime? Is that what this is?

1725
02:09:07,240 --> 02:09:10,492
I'm being charged with a crime?

1726
02:09:10,660 --> 02:09:14,704
This is funny, that's what this is! This is…

1727
02:09:14,872 --> 02:09:18,166
I'm gonna rip the eyes out of your head and piss in your dead skull!

1728
02:09:18,334 --> 02:09:20,252
You fucked with the wrong Marine!

1729
02:09:20,420 --> 02:09:24,881
Colonel Jessep, do you understand your rights?

1730
02:09:29,846 --> 02:09:32,472
You fucking people.

1731
02:09:32,640 --> 02:09:35,517
You have no idea how to defend a nation.

1732
02:09:36,185 --> 02:09:41,148
All you did was weaken a country today, Kaffee. That's all you did.

1733
02:09:41,315 --> 02:09:46,319
You put peoples' lives in danger. Sweet dreams, son.

1734
02:09:46,487 --> 02:09:48,530
Don't call me son.

1735
02:09:48,698 --> 02:09:52,868
I'm a lawyer, and an officer in the United States Navy.

1736
02:09:53,035 --> 02:09:55,871
And you're under arrest, you son of a bitch.

1737
02:10:00,042 --> 02:10:02,169
The witness is excused.

1738
02:10:24,275 --> 02:10:27,736
All rise!

1739
02:10:36,871 --> 02:10:41,583
Have you reached a verdict? We have, sir.

1740
02:10:52,303 --> 02:10:57,849
Lance Corporal Dawson, Private First Class Downey.

1741
02:10:59,018 --> 02:11:03,271
On the charge of murder, the members find the accused

1742
02:11:03,439 --> 02:11:05,690
not guilty.

1743
02:11:06,442 --> 02:11:10,320
On the charge of conspiracy to commit murder,

1744
02:11:10,488 --> 02:11:15,742
the members find the accused not guilty.

1745
02:11:16,619 --> 02:11:20,747
On the charge of conduct unbecoming a United States Marine,

1746
02:11:20,915 --> 02:11:26,836
the members find the accused guilty as charged.

1747
02:11:28,214 --> 02:11:31,466
The accused are sentenced to time already served

1748
02:11:31,634 --> 02:11:36,429
and are ordered to be dishonorably discharged from the Marine Corps.

1749
02:11:37,682 --> 02:11:38,807
This court-martial is adjourned.

1750
02:11:40,226 --> 02:11:41,893
All rise.

1751
02:11:57,493 --> 02:11:59,995
What did that mean?

1752
02:12:01,789 --> 02:12:04,624
Hal?

1753
02:12:04,792 --> 02:12:07,836
What did that mean?

1754
02:12:09,964 --> 02:12:14,301
I don't understand. Colonel Jessep said he ordered the Code Red.

1755
02:12:14,468 --> 02:12:16,845
I know. He said he ordered the Code Red.

1756
02:12:17,013 --> 02:12:19,431
What did we do wrong? It's not that simple.

1757
02:12:19,599 --> 02:12:23,351
We did nothing wrong! Yeah, we did.

1758
02:12:26,439 --> 02:12:31,359
We were supposed to fight for people who couldn't fight for themselves.

1759
02:12:31,527 --> 02:12:34,154
We were supposed to fight for Willy.

1760
02:12:40,536 --> 02:12:46,458
Lieutenant Kaffee, I have to take these men for some paperwork.

1761
02:12:55,426 --> 02:12:58,386
Harold?

1762
02:13:00,514 --> 02:13:03,350
Sir?

1763
02:13:03,517 --> 02:13:06,061
You don't need a patch on your arm to have honor.

1764
02:13:09,774 --> 02:13:14,736
Ten-hut! There's an officer on deck.

1765
02:13:39,553 --> 02:13:44,891
Airmen O'Malley and Rodriguez, what exactly could they testify to?

1766
02:13:45,059 --> 02:13:50,188
Probably that they had absolutely no recollection of anything.

1767
02:13:50,356 --> 02:13:55,193
Strong witnesses. And handsome too, didn't you think?

1768
02:13:55,361 --> 02:13:57,904
I'll see you around. I gotta go arrest Kendrick.

1769
02:13:58,072 --> 02:14:00,532
Tell him I say hi.

1770
02:14:00,700 --> 02:14:04,786
Will do.
